outlooksByWeek.1: Justin Jefferson kicks off the 2024 season looking to build on another stellar campaign despite battling injuries last year. Even with the uncertainty at quarterback, Jefferson remains a premier fantasy option thanks to his exceptional production, finishing Top 10 in yards per route in all four of his seasons. He'll be heavily relied upon as Sam Darnold's primary target in a Minnesota offense that may lean on its star receiver more than ever. Jefferson gets a favorable matchup in Week 1, facing a Giants defense that allowed the fifth-most fantasy points to wide receivers last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Jefferson enters his fifth season with the Vikings after missing significant time due to injury for the first time in his career last season. In his eight healthy games, Jefferson averaged 24 fantasy points per game and was one of only four wide receivers to have at least six games with 23 fantasy points in 2023. In a season where the Vikings started Kirk Cousins, Nick Mullens, Joshua Dobbs and Jaren Hall, Jefferson proved himself QB-proof. This season he'll have Sam Darnold under center. While there could be some growing pains in this offense, Jefferson is one of the few WRs that can make magic happen with subpar QB play. He is once again a top-five fantasy wide receiver.

outlooksByWeek.1: Saquon Barkley stays in the NFC East with a move from the bumbling Giants to Super Bowl contender Philadelphia.  Barkley was injury-prone during his time with the G-Men, but still maintained his explosiveness when healthy, and should benefit from a bevy of weapons around him on the Eagles, rather than being the sole focal point of a mediocre offense as he was in New York.  In Week 1, Barkley will have an extremely favorable matchup versus a  Packers defense that allowed 128.3 rushing yards per tilt in 2023, which was 28th in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: Barkley left the rival Giants for the superior offense down the New Jersey Turnpike, one stacked with elite options at quarterback, wide receiver and, perhaps most importantly, along the still-dominant offensive line. Barkley's 2023 numbers may appear average, but blame the underwhelming New York offense, from the players to its direction. Still blessed with elite skills, a mostly healthy Barkley finished ninth among running backs at 15.9 fantasy points per game, and he may return to his 2022 numbers (1,312 rushing yards, 57 catches) in this top offense. Barkley is a first-round fantasy pick and potential top-three fantasy RB provided health (one never knows) and volume (no problems there).

outlooksByWeek.1: Michael Pittman will look to reprise his role as the top option in the Colts' passing attack in Week 1 against a Texans defense that allowed the 12th-most yards but second-fewest touchdowns (10) to wide receivers in 2023. Pittman has averaged 1,053 receiving yards and 4.7 receiving TDs over the past three seasons, but the Texans held him to a total of 100 yards across two meetings last season. Anthony Richardson is back under center for the Colts after suffering a season-ending shoulder in Week 5 last season, and Indianapolis drafted WR Adonai Mitchell in the second round, but WR Josh Downs (ankle) may not be available against the Texans. Pittman figures to see a lot of cornerback Derek Stingley, who had a strong finish to his second NFL season in 2023 after an up-and-down start to his career.

player.seasonOutlook: A steady career progression as a sure-handed receiver earned Pittman a big extension from the Colts heading into his fifth season. The son of a former bruising running back, Pittman handles a physical, possession role that includes rare volume, as he finished ninth in total targets and fifth in receptions in 2023. A touchdown-per-target rate of just 3.1% as a pro and a modest average depth of target clip the past two seasons have resulted in WR2 outcomes for Pittman. As the likely first read for Anthony Richardson on most dropbacks this season, Pittman enters the season with a stable floor for WR2 production and the upside for a new tier of value. Targeting Pittman after the crop of true WR1 options are taken could prove savvy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Davante Adams proved not to be quarterback-proof after all. After back-to-back seasons of over 1,500 receiving yards despite the fact that he was catching passes from the likes of Derek Carr in 2022, Adams saw his numbers plunge in 2023 as Jimmy Garoppolo, Aidan O'Connell and even Brian Hoyer took turns under center for the Raiders. His 6.5 yards per target and 11.1 yards per reception were his worst averages since 2015, although he did manage to catch triple-digit passes for the fourth straight season. Gardner Minshew won a battle in training camp over O'Connell for the starting QB job, which should provide Las Vegas' game with more stability, but at 31 years old, Adams may not be able to rebound without more help from his quarterback than a journeyman like Minshew can provide. Adams will face a Chargers secondary in Week 1 that finished in the bottom four in receiving touchdowns allowed and yards per target allowed to wideouts last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Considering Adams endured three quarterbacks throwing him the football and a midseason coaching change, his 2023 season was probably better than you remember it being. Adams finished 10th among WRs in fantasy points. He got off to a scorching start, with two 20-point performances in his first three weeks, but suffered an inexplicable, mid-year dip in targets just before Josh McDaniels was dispatched. Under Antonio Pierce, Adams finished strong, posting the league's highest target share (36.4%) and five games of 14-plus fantasy points. It was a reminder that Adams is one of the league's true game-changing receivers, independent of who is throwing him the football. He remains a fantasy WR1 entering his age-31 season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Kenneth Walker is set to start in Week 1 in a great matchup against Denver, who had the third worst rushing defense in the league last season. Walker should operate as Seattle's lead back, though Zach Charbonnet will likely spell Walker at points during the game. New offensive coordinator Ryan Grubb has been full of praise for Walker this offseason, explicitly making note of his improvements in pass protection and his abilities as a pass-catcher. Walker is already a strong fantasy option with his ability to rip off long runs, so any additional pass-catching work would serve as a welcome bonus. Denver didn't make many improvements to their defense this offseason after allowing a league high 5.0 yards per rushing attempt in 2023.

player.seasonOutlook: There was concern that Seattle would revert to utilizing an RBBC after selecting UCLA's Zach Charbonnet in the second round of the 2023 draft. While Walker and Charbonnet logged an even number of snaps, Walker remained the team's primary option, averaging nearly 15 carries and two catches per contest for the season. Despite demonstrating high-end burst and change-of-direction ability (72 evaded tackles, RB3), Walker struggled with efficiency (4.1 YPC). His receiving chops also remain in question, as he drew fewer targets and posted a lower catch rate (78.4%, RB22) than the aforementioned Charbonnet. Still, Walker figures to lead Seattle's backfield and should deliver RB2 numbers for fantasy managers in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Trey McBride will open the season as Arizona's starting tight end in a Week 1 visit to Buffalo, where he figures to feature prominently after logging just over 7 receptions per game in the second half of the 2023 season. The Bills have a good passing defense, and they allowed just under 45 receiving yards to tight ends per game last season, 8th best in the NFL. McBride led the Cardinals with 106 targets last season, which was 7th best among tight ends. While McBride now has to compete with rookie Marvin Harrison for opportunities, he still should be frequently targeted as Kyler Murray's secondary target in the Cardinals' offense.

player.seasonOutlook: McBride put together a breakout sophomore effort, leading all Arizona pass-catchers in targets (108), receptions (81) and yards (825). The Colorado State product averaged more than eight targets per contest from Weeks 8 through 18, after Zach Ertz was placed on injured reserve and eventually waived. McBride quickly earned Kyler Murray's trust, drawing a team-high five end zone looks and recording a catch rate of 80% over the final eight games of the season. He figures to remain an integral part of the Cardinals' aerial attack heading into 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Dak Prescott is coming off arguably his best season for the Cowboys.  Despite the lack of postseason success, Prescott has shined otherwise, throwing for over 4,500 yards for the second time in his career, surpassing 35 passing touchdowns while limiting his interceptions (just nine in 2023). Prescott likely also gave a huge sigh of relief when CeeDee Lamb was re-signed to a massive deal.  However, in Week 1, Dallas will likely face a stiff test versus a Cleveland defense that allowed the fewest passing yards in the NFL in 2023.

player.seasonOutlook: Prescott bounced back last season after a challenging 2022, finishing third among QBs in fantasy points, and he was one of only four passers to average 20 fantasy points per game. Volume is key. No quarterback completed more passes and Prescott's 36 touchdown passes were four more than anyone else. While Prescott's long-term future in Dallas may be problematic, he is safe this season and enjoys CeeDee Lamb to throw to. Prescott has delivered exceptional statistics when healthy (2019, 2021, 2023), so while he may slip outside the top five quarterbacks on draft day, it only makes him a bargain.

outlooksByWeek.1: Rashee Rice made a big impact for the Super Bowl champions in 2023 after being selected in the second round of the 2023 Draft. The SMU product became a big yards-after-catch weapon for Kansas City, turning bubble screens and underneath routes into big gains and just missing a 1,000-yard campaign. Legal troubles hang over his head, but Rice seems as though he will avoid punishment from the league until his case is concluded, which may not happen until next offseason. Rice figures to be one of Patrick Mahomes' top targets in Week 1 against a Ravens secondary that ranked eighth in 2023 in receiving yards allowed to wideouts.

player.seasonOutlook: Rice was arguably the one thing that went right in a 2023 Chiefs wide receiver room that seemed to get everything else wrong. He delivered 212.5 fantasy points (eighth best among all rookies) and had seven top-25 positional weekly scores. Though he did most of his damage in the short game -- his 4.9 aDOT was lowest among wide receivers -- he quickly developed into a go-to target for Patrick Mahomes. Rice was WR8 in the season's final seven weeks, despite sitting out Week 18. Rice is tricky to rank, as he could be facing a multi-game suspension due to an off-the-field incident, but he has WR2 value when active. His usage should be similar to 2023 even after the team's offseason addition of deep threats Marquise Brown and Xavier Worthy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Christian Kirk hurt his calf in August, but he has resumed practicing and seems on track to suit up in Week 1 against a Dolphins defense that allowed 17 touchdowns to wide receivers in 2023, tied for sixth-most in the NFL. Kirk had 1,108 receiving yards in 2022 and was on pace for nearly the exact same total through 12 games in 2023 before suffering a season-ending groin injury. He should pick up where he left off despite changes to the wide receiver room around him, as the Jaguars lost Calvin Ridley and Zay Jones in free agency but signed Gabe Davis and drafted Brian Thomas 23rd overall. Miami lost cornerback Xavien Howard and safety Brandon Jones in the offseason but signed CB Kendall Fuller and S Jordan Poyer.

player.seasonOutlook: A return to the top of the depth chart in Jacksonville could define Kirk's 2024. Calvin Ridley's arrival in Jacksonville last season saw Kirk assume a smaller share of the passing market, resulting in per-game production in the WR3 and flex tier among receivers. A core injury that required surgery and an IR stint also slowed his production. This marked a decline from Kirk's surprisingly strong WR2 finish in his 2022 debut season with the team. Yet with Ridley off to the rival Titans and the arrival of lower-volume field-stretcher Gabe Davis and rookie Brian Thomas Jr., Kirk has a realistic path to pace the depth chart in opportunities as a top option for Trevor Lawrence. Consider Kirk as a flex.

outlooksByWeek.1: Raheem Mostert's nose for the end zone will be tested when the Dolphins face the Jaguars in Week 1. Mostert is off a career year, topping 1,000 yards for the first time while scoring 18 touchdowns after collecting 14 in his previous 11 seasons, combined. He'll again split carries with De'Von Achane and potentially rookie Jaylen Wright, and last season's pace would seemingly be unsustainable despite the Dolphins' elite offense. Jacksonville ranked ninth in rushing yards allowed and surrendered just 15 touchdowns on the ground last year.

player.seasonOutlook: Mostert, now in his third season with the Dolphins, is a 32-year-old running back coming off a career year. He led the league in rushing touchdowns (18) and surpassed 200 rushing attempts and 1,000 rushing yards for the first time. Despite sharing the workload with exceptional rookie De'Von Achane, Mostert remains a key part of the explosive Dolphins offense, and our projections suggest Miami will continue with the committee approach. Mostert is extremely unlikely to approach last season's touchdown count, but should be viewed as a high-end flex option.

Pittsburgh checked in as the No. 11 D/ST last season, and it finished just outside of the top 10 in sacks and interceptions. The Steelers feature one of the best edge rushing combos in the NFL with T.J. Watt (league-best 19 sacks) and Alex Highsmith, and the addition of linebacker Patrick Queen elevates the second level of the defense. With Minkah Fitzpatrick anchoring the secondary, and a pressure-oriented scheme that can heat up the pocket, the Steelers project as a top-10 fantasy defense in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Evan McPherson will begin his fourth season as the Bengals' kicker heading into a Week 1 matchup against New England. He hit 84 percent of his field-goal attempts in 2023 and did not miss any kicks inside of 50 yards. McPherson and the Bengals will face a Patriots' defense that should be strong, keyed by the linebacker corps as well as the secondary. Even so, fantasy managers should be confident that McPherson will deliver when called upon.

player.seasonOutlook: McPherson converted 83.9% of field goal attempts last season, while hitting seven of 12 from 50-plus yards. He was perfect on extra points and he finished the season with 135 fantasy points. With a healthy Joe Burrow back to lead an explosive Bengals offense, McPherson should produce top-10 numbers this season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Caleb Williams, the No. 1 overall pick in the 2024 draft, begins his career with the Bears as the franchise quarterback. Surrounded by an upgraded cast that includes wideouts DJ Moore, Keenan Allen, and rookie Rome Odunze, as well as pass-catching back D'Andre Swift and steady tight end Cole Kmet, Williams has a wealth of weapons at his disposal. His elite arm and mobility make him a dynamic playmaker with the potential to become the Bears' first 4,000-yard passer in franchise history. In Week 1, Williams will debut at Soldier Field against the Titans, a defense that allowed the 11th-fewest fantasy points to opposing QBs but accumulated the fewest interceptions in the league last season.

player.seasonOutlook: The Bears selected Williams with the first pick in the 2024 NFL draft. He was stellar at USC, showcasing his natural playmaking ability both in and out of the pocket, finishing with a single-season school record with 4,919 yards passing. In Chicago, he joins an offense that was second in rushing yards and attempts while also finishing bottom six in passing yards, passing attempts and completions last season. Part of that rushing total came from the departed Justin Fields, and Shane Waldron is now calling plays, so this offense should be more balanced in 2024. Williams will have a strong supporting cast with DJ Moore, Keenan Allen and Rome Odunze leading the way, but he's best viewed as a mid-tier QB2 with upside in his rookie season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jerome Ford enters the season in position to lead the Browns' backfield in a Week 1 matchup against Dallas with Nick Chubb still sidelined while recovering from a torn ACL. Ford got a similar opportunity last season after Chubb suffered the injury, though his outlook should be improved due to a lack of alternative options on the running back depth chart. Unlike its stingy pass defense, Dallas struggled to limit opponents in the rushing game last season by allowing 114.1 yards per game. Ford's fantasy value is likely to decline as the season progresses and Chubb returns, but he sets up for a strong performance in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: Ford enters his third season with the Browns after posting career highs in rushing and receving yards in 2023. In relief of Nick Chubb (knee) during the Week 2 game versus the Steelers, Ford dropped 24.1 fantasy points on the Pittsburgh defense, while he averaged 12.9 points from Weeks 3 through 17. Ford has the lateral agility and power to shed tacklers, plus the straight-line speed to create explosive plays in the run and pass game. With the uncertainty of Chubb's recovery from injury, Ford should be drafted in all formats with the potential upside of taking on a volume role this season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Bijan Robinson was surprisingly underutilized as a rookie last season, but beginning with Atlanta's matchup against a tough Steelers front in Week 1, he now projects for the workhorse role that his 215-plus pound, and 4.46-second 40 build and former No. 8 overall draft capital demands. Pittsburgh is a tough Week 1 opponent that last season was more vulnerable through the air than up front, but Robinson's three-down skillset makes him capable of overcoming even the most difficult matchups. In addition to working as Atlanta's top ball carrier, with Tyler Allgeier now relegated to a true backup role, Robinson could do most of his damage Week 1 as one of new quarterback Kirk Cousins' favorite pass-catchers in the intermediate area of the field.

player.seasonOutlook: Robinson's rookie season was a mixed bag that included limited rushing contributions (15th or lower in carries, yards and TDs) but excellent receiving production (top five among RBs in routes, targets, yards and TDs), as well as terrific efficiency. Robinson's season felt underwhelming considering his early-first-round pedigree, but he finished fifth among RBs in snaps, sixth in yards and ninth in fantasy points. With Kirk Cousins now under center and Zac Robinson replacing run-heavy Arthur Smith as the team's play caller, a leap forward for Robinson seems likely in his second campaign. That will especially be the case if he manages more work near the goal line (only two carries inside the 5-yard line in 2023). Robinson should be one of the first RBs off the board on draft day.

outlooksByWeek.1: Garrett Wilson will look to breakout for the Jets, starting in Week 1 against the 49ers Monday night. Wilson has turned in consecutive 1,000 yard seasons since being drafted out of Ohio State, both coming with mediocre quarterback play. That could change with Aaron Rodgers now healthy, and seemingly minimal competition for volume targets elsewhere. New York has deep threat Mike Williams currently healthy and a workhorse RB in Breece Hall, but not much else, suggesting Wilson will be peppered early and often. This won't be an easy opener with San Francisco allowing a mere 6.4 ypc and the presence of top CB Charvarius Ward, but Wilson likely embraces that challenge and can produce on volume alone.

player.seasonOutlook: Wilson is entering his third season with the Jets, with fantasy managers eagerly anticipating his breakout season. Since Wilson joined the league, New York's quarterback unit has yet to exceed a passer rating of 75. Despite this, Wilson has already broken the Jets' franchise records for most receiving yards (1,956) and receptions (159) in his first two seasons. He has also maintained an impressive average of 9.2 targets per game, a reliable metric for wide receivers. Even with Mike Williams added to the fold, Wilson has the potential for a career-best performance in 2024 with Aaron Rodgers returning under center. Projected to lead the Jets in targets, Wilson can be confidently drafted as a low-end WR1 in fantasy drafts.

outlooksByWeek.1: Isiah Pacheco took on a more significant role in the Kansas City offense in his second NFL season, averaging 14.6 carries over 14 regular-season games (up from 10.0 a game as a rookie) and just missing his first career 1,000-yard rushing campaign. The Rutgers product's physical running style did lead to a couple missed games due to injuries, but he has plenty of holes to hit working behind the team's excellent offensive line and against defenses forced to account for Patrick Mahomes. Pacheco could see an even bigger workload early in the 2024 season with Clyde Edwards-Helaire out for at least the first four games, and only undrafted rookie Carson Steele and late signing Samaje Perine as backups. Pacheco will face a Ravens defense in Week 1 that tied for the league lead by allowing only five rushing TDs to running backs in 2023, but also showed a vulnerability to chunk plays by giving up 4.47 yards per carry to RBs, 27th in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: If Pacheco's rookie campaign was the one that put him on the fantasy map, his sophomore year was the one that earned him star status. His 15.3 fantasy points per game were nearly double his 2022 number (7.9), and he surged late in the season, scoring 20-plus points in three of his final four regular-season games before totaling 373 yards and three touchdowns on 93 touches during the Chiefs' Super Bowl championship run. Most importantly, Pacheco handled seven of the team's 10 goal line carries and 16 of 23 carries in goal-to-go situations, establishing himself the clear primary rusher. He's a fantasy RB1 and should settle in as a near-universal second-round pick.

outlooksByWeek.1: Alvin Kamara enters his eighth season with the Saints with a favorable Week 1 matchup against Carolina on deck, and as this team's unquestioned top backfield option. While Kamara's rushing totals have dropped every year since 2020, it's notable that his one game against the Panthers last season was his most efficient of the year, at 4.7 yards per carry. New Orleans' offensive line has lost three starters in Andrus Peat, James Hurst and Ryan Ramczyk from last season, and though that could hamper Kamara's efficiency as a rusher, it could paradoxically boost his production if Derek Carr is forced to regularly pivot plays towards an emergency dump-off pass. Kamara buoyed his production with 75 receptions in 13 game last season, and as efficiency is no longer his call to fame, volume may have to do for the 29-year-old this season.

player.seasonOutlook: Kamara had a career-low 694 rush yards on just 3.9 yards per carry last season, but he was still an effective receiver (75 receptions) despite being 29 years old, and he finished as RB11. He was able to hold off rookie Kendre Miller, who was often injured last season, but we expect Miller to make a bigger impact this season. The versatile Taysom Hill is also probably going to eat into Kamara's production, further clouding his outlook. Kamara was ninth in the league in red zone touches and should still be a go-to option, but the days of him being one of the first RBs off the board are over. He's now a low-end RB1, and the aforementioned TD vultures will be bothersome to his fantasy managers this season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Brandon Aiyuk recently re-signed with the 49ers after holding out for most of the offseason. He's ready to resume his starting role, but his Week 1 matchup against the Jets will be one of the most difficult of the entire season. The Jets held opponents to under 190 receiving yards per game in 2023, 3rd best in the league. Coach Kyle Shannahan is excellent at scheming his best playmakers open, but Aiyuk will have to deal with coverage from a strong Jets secondary that includes talented corners Sauce Gardner and Michael Carter. Aiyuk is capable of putting up big fantasy games, but his floor is lower than usual in this difficult matchup.

player.seasonOutlook: While Aiyuk didn't draw a ton of targets relative to the position (105, WR30), he did materialize as the 49ers' most peppered pass-catcher, registering 21 more looks and eight more grabs than Christian McCaffrey. Aiyuk's next-level efficiency and career-best YPR (17.9, WR2) buoyed his volume and provided fantasy managers with regular double-digit fantasy totals. A regression remains reasonable to expect heading into 2024, but Aiyuk is a primary target in an elite offense and, thus, a solid WR2 target.

outlooksByWeek.1: C.J. Stroud's sophomore season begins on the road against the AFC South rival Colts in Week 1. Stroud threw for 4,108 yards with a 23:5 TD:INT in a highly successful rookie regular season for the Texans after being selected second overall in the 2023 NFL Draft. That success included 648 yards and a 4:0 TD:INT in two games against the Colts, whom the Texans beat on the road in Week 18 last season with a playoff berth on the line. Houston traded for six-time 1,000-yard receiver Stefon Diggs while bringing back its top three receiving yards leaders from last season (WRs Nico Collins and Tank Dell, plus TE Dalton Schultz). Indianapolis allowed the fifth-most points per game last season (24.4) and didn't make significant personnel changes on defense, bringing back all 10 players that made double-digit starts on that side of the ball.

player.seasonOutlook: The former Buckeye looks to build on a momentous first season that included becoming just the fifth rookie quarterback to ever throw for at least 4,000 yards. Without much rushing volume or success in either his collegiate or professional profile, Stroud's fantasy production will be defined by his proficiency from the pocket. After finishing seventh in per-game fantasy output last season, another prolific passing season could unfold given the presence of a trio of talented receivers -- Nico Collins, Stefon Diggs and Tank Dell -- each of whom brings special route trees and skill sets to the field. Securing Stroud in the middle rounds is a sound strategy for those who wait a bit at the position.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jaylen Waddle enters Week 1 for the Dolphins with a clean bill of health as they prepare to face the Jaguars. Waddle has been dealing with an undisclosed injury throughout the preseason, but will reprise his ying to Tyreek Hill's yang in what is a very clear, two man passing funnel for Miami. Waddle has three-straight 1,000 yards seasons, and while Hill gets the accolades for his big play prowess, Waddle too has averaged at least 14.1 ypc over the last two seasons. He saw 8+ targets in eight games last season, all coming over the his last 12 games. Jacksonville's defense allowed a modest 7.1 ypa, but were prone to big plays, which is right in this offense's wheelhouse.

player.seasonOutlook: Waddle has been superb since being selected sixth overall in the 2021 NFL draft. Since Tyreek Hill came to Miami two seasons ago, Waddle has averaged 7.0 targets and 14.7 fantasy points per game. He's also been very efficient over that time frame, catching 66.5% of his targets. In 2023, under head coach and playcaller Mike McDaniel, the Dolphins' offense was second in passing yards per game. That trend should continue in 2024 and Waddle will be actively involved. He's projected for the second-most targets on the team behind Hill and is a fringe fantasy WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Zamir White saw a big increase in touches in his second season as the primary backup to Josh Jacobs, averaging 4.3 yards per carry and showing the ability to be a lead back late in the year when he racked up 397 rushing yards over the final four weeks. The Raiders elected to give him the job, letting Jacobs walk in free agency and adding little in the way of reinforcements, with former Viking backup Alexander Mattison and 2024 sixth-round pick Dylan Laube now bolstering the depth chart. White has the size and physical running style to be a punishing presence on early downs and should get goal-line opportunities, but he'll likely cede obvious passing down work to Laube. White will face a Chargers defense in Week 1 that finished 2023 in the middle of the pack in rushing yards, rushing TDs and yards per carry allowed to RBs.

player.seasonOutlook: After spending 27 games as a scarcely used backup to Josh Jacobs, White finally got his chance to strut his stuff beginning in Week 15 last season, after Jacobs was lost to a quadriceps injury. White rushed a league-high 84 times during his four-game audition, ranked fourth with 457 yards from scrimmage and 2.33 average yards after first contact, and was eighth among RBs in fantasy points per game in that span (15.2). It set the power back up nicely for a leading role in 2024, despite the Raiders' offseason addition of Alexander Mattison. White could have fantasy RB2 value on a matchups basis.

outlooksByWeek.1: Dallas Goedert set a career-high with 59 receptions last season, but managed just 592 yards en route to a career-low 10 yards per reception. Goedert has been consistent during his Eagles career, gaining over 500 yards receiving in five-straight seasons, while scoring at least three touchdowns in all six NFL campaigns.  Still, he has fallen short of lofty expectations since Zach Ertz left town, and the Eagles have a bevy of other weapons which limit his upside.  In Week 1, Philadelphia will face a Packers defense that was fairly stingy against the pass in 2023, allowing just 206.8 yards per tilt through the air, which was ninth in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: The consistent Goedert enters his seventh season still looking to truly break out for fantasy purposes. A broken forearm cost him three games last season, and he missed five games during the team's Super Bowl season. Goedert still hasn't reached 60 receptions in any season, and he has been held to three touchdowns in three of the past four, as he barely gets a look at the goal line. The efficiency we saw from him in 2021 and 2022 ceased last season, as his yards per target dropped from 10.2 to 7.1. Quality depth at tight end in fantasy has improved in recent years, so Goedert is more of a borderline TE1 and late-round pick than coveted asset.

outlooksByWeek.1: Xavier Worthy set a Combine record by posting a time of 4.21 seconds in the 40-yard dash, and that performance, along with his strong college production, caused Kansas City to nab him with the 28th overall pick in the 2024 Draft. Tyreek Hill comparisons are inevitable given the team he ended up with, and Worthy could prove to be a similarly dangerous deep threat while hauling in passes from Patrick Mahomes behind overmatched cornerbacks. The Texas product has a lot to prove against NFL defenders given his tiny frame, but his aptitude on bubble screens fits nicely into Andy Reid's offensive scheme. His main competition for deep targets, Marquise Brown, is also dealing with a shoulder injury to begin the season, putting Worthy in position to make an immediate impact in Week 1 even against a stingy Ravens secondary that led the league in 2023 by allowing just 6.20 yards per target to wideouts.

player.seasonOutlook: That the Chiefs paid handsomely to move up to 28th overall in the NFL draft to select Worthy speaks volumes about their regard for his big-play ability. In his final season at Texas, he averaged 7.7 yards after the catch per target and broke 15 tackles, and he ultimately broke the 40-yard dash record at the NFL combine (4.21 seconds). Though the Chiefs' receiving depth should afford them patience with Worthy's development, his ability to stretch the field will prove handy to them from Day 1. If he clicks, he could deliver fantasy WR3 numbers right from the start. Bear in mind, however, that players of his ilk often have their single-game statistical peaks and valleys.

outlooksByWeek.1: Brock Purdy faces a Jets defense in Week 1 that was one of the league's best last season, allowing less than 190 passing yards per game in 2023. Kyle Shannahan likely will continue to rely on an intermediate passing game where Purdy gets the ball into the hands of the many 49ers playmakers who are skilled at earning yards after the catch. Brandon Aiyuk finally re-signed, ending his offseason holdout and giving Purdy a full arsenal of receiving options. Purdy likely won't throw deep much in this matchup, but if he receivers get loose, he could put up decent numbers.

player.seasonOutlook: Purdy returned from UCL surgery by fending off (theoretical) competition at the position and putting together a breakout effort in 2023. Surrounded by elite YAC talent, serving in an ultra-friendly scheme and buoyed by a solid defense, Mr. Irrelevant didn't always have to do a whole lot to win games. That sometimes meant underwhelming numbers from a fantasy perspective, though Purdy did average more than 18 fantasy points per contest and finished inside the top 10 among fantasy QBs. He's not the most dynamic player, but his situation provides him (and fake football managers) with a wonderfully high floor. He projects to post fringe-QB1 fantasy numbers again in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tyjae Spears has a Week 1 matchup against a Bears defense that allowed the third-fewest rushing yards to running backs last season but surrendered the most receiving yards in the NFL to the position. Spears' skill set matches up well against Chicago's linebackers, who are much better at filling running lanes than dropping into coverage. He had 838 scrimmage yards on 100 carries and 52 catches as a rookie last season while working in a change-of-pace role behind Derrick Henry. The Titans replaced Henry with Tony Pollard in the offseason, and while the 215-pound Pollard is closer in build to the 200-pound Spears, the breakdown in touches is likely to be closer to even in Tennessee's new-look backfield.

player.seasonOutlook: Spears enters his second NFL season, with Derrick Henry out and Tony Pollard in as his competition for touches. This third-round pick capably handled the ninth-most targets among backs, on the way to more than 800 scrimmage yards in an impressive rookie season. Spears' production as a receiving valve for Will Levis last season offers encouraging evidence he can again excel in a timeshare this season. Given the immense value of targets compared to carries and the natural expectation for Spears to take on more overall work this season, the arrow is pointing up for him as a mid-round RB2/flex option.

The Bengals produced just 5.4 fantasy points per game last season (24th at D/ST), while surrendering a league high in both yards per play (6.1) and yards per pass attempt (8.2). The club added defensive tackle Sheldon Rankins in free agency, as well as safety Geno Stone, after he logged seven interceptions in Baltimore last season. That's a boost for proven defensive coordinator Lou Anarumo. However, the Bengals will need to limit opposing offenses at a much higher rate this season to be considered a borderline top-10 fantasy defense.

outlooksByWeek.1: Ka'imi Fairbairn begins his eighth season as Houston's kicker in Week 1 against a Colts team that allowed 24.4 points per game last season, fifth-most in the NFL. Lucas Oil Stadium has a retractable roof, so Fairbairn will have good conditions in which to kick. Fairbairn has been one of the league's most accurate kickers over the past two seasons, connecting on 56 of 59 field-goal attempts. Houston's offense is expected to get into scoring range frequently as second-year QB C.J. Stroud commands a passing attack that added six-time 1,000-yard receiver Stefon Diggs.

player.seasonOutlook: A gifted kicker entering his eighth season with the Texans, Fairbairn was limited to a dozen regular-season games last season due to a quad injury. While active, he averaged 2.3 field goal attempts per game, a pace that would have seen him finish third in the NFL had he sustained it over a full 17-game schedule. Of the 33 kickers with at least 17 field goal attempts last season, Fairbairn's 96.7% conversion clip rated second only to Nick Folk. Tied to an ascendant Houston offense and with a leg that merits trust from all over the field from his coaching staff, it makes sense to consider Fairbairn among the better fantasy options at this often fickle position.

outlooksByWeek.1: Christian McCaffrey sustained a calf injury this offseason, but the 49ers have not expressed any concern that he won't be available against the Jets in Week 1. The Jets have one of the best defenses in the NFL and allowed just 3.99 yards per carry to running backs in 2023. That said, even the best defenses in the league have their hands full containing McCaffrey, a true workhorse back who racked up over 125 yards from scrimmage per game in 2023. Even with slightly lowered expectations in a tough matchup, McCaffrey remains a top shelf fantasy option this weekend.

player.seasonOutlook: McCaffrey recorded the most fantasy points per game (24.5) and the third-most fantasy points overall (391) among all players last season. He ranked inside the top three fantasy producers at the position in nearly every statistical category -- from rushing yards (1,459, RB1) and receiving yards (564, RB2) to evaded tackles (77, RB1) and total TDs (21, RB1) -- the 28-year-old stayed healthy for a second straight season. McCaffrey is the centerpiece of the 49ers' explosive offense and he deserves to be at the top of draft boards this summer.

outlooksByWeek.1: Puka Nacua has been a full participant in recent practices after suffering a knee injury in early August, and he is ready to start for the Rams in Week 1 at the Lions. While Detroit added much needed help to their secondary this offseason, they have a long way to go after allowing 28 receiving touchdowns in 2023, sixth worst in the NFL.  The return of a healthy Cooper Kupp might hurt Nacua's ceiling somewhat, but he still averaged over 8 targets per game when Kupp was active last season. Nacua remains a strong fantasy option to open the season.

player.seasonOutlook: Rostered in just 1.6% of ESPN Fantasy leagues ahead of Week 1 last season, Nacua proved to be the waiver wire's most generous offering. The first-year slotman immediately filled injured Cooper Kupp's shoes to lead the team in routes, targets, catches and yards, while regularly dazzling after the catch (639 YAC, WR5). Nacua's volume dipped after Kupp returned, but the BYU product continued to churn, setting both the NFL rookie receiving yards and receptions records. Given Kupp's age and injury history, Nacua is a good bet to remain Matthew Stafford's most productive pass-catcher again in 2024. He's a solid fantasy WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Kyren Williams is expected to be the Rams' primary running back in Week 1, despite the addition of rookie Blake Corum. Williams faces a Lions defense that was strong against the run in 2023, allowing just 3.47 yards per carry. Still, the Rams' matchup against the Lions projects to be high scoring, and the Lions were involved in several shootouts at home last season. Williams may concede some snaps to Corum, but his three-down skill set makes him a solid fantasy option.

player.seasonOutlook: After injuries kept Williams off the field in 2022, he entered his sophomore effort barely drafted by fantasy managers (14th-round ADP in 12-team PPR leagues). That quickly changed as Williams emerged as the Rams' undisputed RB1, averaging nearly 22 touches per contest in his 12 games played. A creative runner with receiving chops and an uncanny nose for the end zone (15 total TDs, third among RBs), Williams turned on the jets down the stretch, posting nearly 24 fantasy points per game from Weeks 12 through 17. He did break his hand during the team's Wild Card game in Detroit, but should be healed up in time for training camp. Fantasy managers will want to keep an eye on rookie Blake Corum's potential ascent, but Williams remains the lead back and is a solid RB1 target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Rachaad White's third season with the Buccaneers kicks off at home against a vulnerable Washington defense Week 1. After having been a big part of Tampa Bay's offensive resurgence last season, White remains locked in as the top option in the backfield. His efficiency as a pass-catcher was elite in 2023, securing 64 of 70 targets for 549 yards and three touchdowns, and the Commanders' defense ranked dead last in the NFL last season in both points and yards allowed. The Buccaneers' upgrades to the interior of the O-line could now position White to take a step forward as a rusher, which was one area he struggled last season, and at 6-0, 214 pounds, he still profiles as the better goal-line option compared to rookie fourth-round pick Bucky Irving (5-9, 192 pounds).

player.seasonOutlook: White returns as the lead back in Tampa, entering his third season. He was the RB4 in fantasy scoring last season, racking up solid rushing yards, showing off his receiving skills and scoring nine total touchdowns. The Bucs made minimal changes behind White on the depth chart this offseason, with fourth-round pick Bucky Irving the most notable addition. Irving could earn his way into some work, but White outperformed expectations last season and should maintain a featured role. White has the look of a value pick once the big names are off the board in your league.

outlooksByWeek.1: Malik Nabers enters his rookie campaign with sky-high expectations for the New York Giants.  Nabers flashed his electric playmaking skills during preseason, and his size, speed and athleticism should translate immediately to the NFL.  The one caveat for Nabers will be if inconsistent quarterback Daniel Jones can get him the ball.  In Week 1, Nabers and company will face a Minnesota Vikings defense that was suspect against the pass in 2023, allowing 234.5 yards per tilt through the air, which was 24th in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: The Giants desperately needed an offensive gamebreaker with big-play ability at wide receiver, someone they can line up anywhere, and they got it by securing Nabers with the sixth overall pick in the April draft. Nabers dominated at LSU, averaging better than 12 yards per target in his final season, and with a huge target share, but things are quite different in the Giants' offense. They struggle to throw the football downfield with Daniel Jones at QB. Nabers has the skills to change the offense and become a fantasy star, but it is tough to recommend him as more than WR3 initially.

outlooksByWeek.1: Evan Engram and the Jaguars will face the Dolphins on the road in Week 1. Miami allowed the 11th-most yards to tight ends last season while tying for the seventh-most receptions and sixth-most touchdowns allowed to the position. Engram led all NFL TEs with 114 catches in 2023, and he's poised to see plenty of attention from QB Trevor Lawrence in this favorable matchup while the Jaguars integrate new additions Gabe Davis and Brian Thomas into their WR room, which lost Calvin Ridley and Zay Jones. Christian Kirk is still around to compete with Engram for short and intermediate targets over the middle, but Kirk has missed some practice time recently due to a calf injury.

player.seasonOutlook: Can Engram match an awesome 2023 that saw him finish just two catches shy of Jimmy Smith's single-season franchise record for receptions? Adding to the historic nature of last season, Engram also produced the fewest yards ever for a player with at least 114 catches, so there's that. Engram's constant command of Trevor Lawrence's attention led to a career year, in which he finished as TE2. Gone are Calvin Ridley's 136 targets from last season, so Engram is again set for a sizable stake in this passing game in 2024. Even with some regression possible in the target and reception departments, Engram is the rare early-round tight end in fantasy with an entirely reasonable projection for at least 120 looks in this offense.

outlooksByWeek.1: Anthony Richardson kicks off his second NFL season with a Week 1 home game against the Texans, who allowed the 10th-most passing yards per game in 2023. The fourth overall pick in the 2023 NFL Draft had three passing touchdowns and four rushing touchdowns in four games before suffering a season-ending shoulder injury in Week 5 of his rookie season. Richardson's dual-threat skill set coupled with star RB Jonathan Taylor gives the Colts' rushing attack immense upside, but questions remain about the big-armed QB's accuracy as a passer. Even if Josh Downs (ankle) is unavailable against Houston, the addition of rookie second-round pick Adonai Mitchell to holdovers Michael Pittman and Alec Pierce in the wide receiver room gives Richardson plenty of weapons in the passing game. The Texans have five new projected starters on defense.

player.seasonOutlook: Football fans are rightfully excited for this dual-threat signal-caller's second season. From Cam Newton to Josh Allen, Lamar Jackson and Jalen Hurts, there is a growing legacy of young quarterbacks thriving as fantasy forces thanks to what some deem the cheat code: Rushing for immense value from behind center. Based on his first three games in the NFL, Richardson was on pace for more than 700 rushing yards with double-digit touchdown production on the ground. After missing 13 games due to a shoulder injury, the natural question is whether Richardson's play style is sustainable on this hard-hitting stage. What isn't in doubt is whether the versatile talent is capable of delivering fun fantasy lines, as last year's small sample suggests is entirely possible. The risks are real, yet the rewards of drafting Richardson as a QB1 in the early-to-middle rounds could be league-altering.

outlooksByWeek.1: George Pickens solidified himself as an elite big-play receiver for the Steelers in 2023, averaging 18.1 yards per catch while 22 of his 63 receptions went for more than 20 yards. Things will look different heading into a Week 1 matchup against Atlanta, as Pickens takes over as the clear top receiver in Pittsburgh after the team dealt away Diontae Johnson during the offseason. In addition, he should have an upgrade at quarterback as Russell Wilson takes over for Kenny Pickett and Mason Rudolph under center. Despite those positives, the Falcons were a stingy defense against opposing wide receivers last season, as they allowed the sixth-fewest receiving yards and eighth-fewest fantasy points per game.

player.seasonOutlook: Heading into his third pro season, Pickens is the unquestioned top target in Pittsburgh after the club traded Diontae Johnson to Carolina. Last season, Pickens averaged 13.2 PPG, despite having inconsistent quarterback play. He flashed his big-play ability, as he logged four games of 20 or more points, including a season-high 35.5 against the Bengals in Week 16. Given his vertical ability (14 receptions on throws of 20 or more air yards), Pickens has real fantasy potential if the Steelers can get a higher level of play at quarterback from either Russell Wilson or Justin Fields. You can draft Pickens as a flex, but he certainly has the ability to produce breakout games that can win you a week.

outlooksByWeek.1: Amari Cooper will kick off the 2024 season with a Week 1 matchup against his former team, the Dallas Cowboys. He has 128 and 132 targets in his two seasons with the Browns, respectively, and should remain the primary target of quarterback Deshaun Watson once again. That doesn't guarantee immediate success, however, as Cooper faces a tough Dallas secondary that allowed the seventh-fewest fantasy points per game to opposing wide receivers in 2023 and also welcomes back Trevon Diggs. Nevertheless, Cooper has a locked-in role and has topped 1,000 receiving yards in four of his last five seasons.

player.seasonOutlook: Cooper is entering his 11th pro season, and third with the Browns. One of the top route technicians in the league, Cooper averaged 14.5 PPG last season (WR16), highlighted by his 51.5-point performance in Week 16 versus the Texans. Cooper has now seen 100 or more targets in five straight seasons, with at least 68 receptions each year during that stretch. The Browns traded for wide receiver Jerry Jeudy, but Cooper will remain the top target in Cleveland's schemed pass game. You can draft Cooper as a reliable flex option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Najee Harris will begin the final season of his rookie contract with a Week 1 matchup against Atlanta. He should lead the Steelers in carries, and he posted his most efficient season on the ground in 2023, averaging 4.1 yards per carry while gaining at least 20 yards on eight separate attempts. On the other hand, Jaylen Warren has cut into Harris' receiving work significantly, dinging his value in PPR formats. It won't be an easy start to the season for Harris either, as the Falcons allowed only five touchdowns on the ground last campaign.

player.seasonOutlook: A true volume grinder, Harris returns to Pittsburgh for his fourth season as the primary runner on early downs. Harris has totaled at least 255 carries and 1,000 rush yards for three straight seasons. However, Harris dipped to 11.4 fantasy points per game last season (RB26), and his receving totals continue to decline (career-low 29 receptions in 2023). A run-heavy approach from new offensive coordinator Arthur Smith is a bonus here, but with the expanding role for Jaylen Warren in the Steelers' backfield, Harris should be targeted as lower-tier flex only.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jaylen Warren broke out in 2023 with the Steelers and will look to replicate his results in 2024 starting with a Week 1 matchup against Atlanta. He suffered an injury scare when he strained his hamstring in preseason action, but Warren has since returned to practice and is planning to suit up to open the campaign. Warren will likely still lag behind Najee Harris in rushing attempts, but he is a strong contributor as a receiver and is also a solid change of pace to Harris on the ground. It won't be an easy matchup for either back in Week 1, as the Falcons allowed only five rushing touchdowns for the entire 2023 campaign.

player.seasonOutlook: Now entering his third pro season, Warren emerged as a playmaking talent with the Steelers in 2023, posting career highs across the board in rushing and receving. Warren posted a run of 10 or more yards on 15.5% of his carries, while producing double-digit fantasy points in 10 of 15 games played. He's an explosive mover, with perimeter juice and the open-field vision to produce as a screen target (18 receptions, 114 yards on screens last season). While Warren will share backfield touches with Najee Harris, he brings more fantasy upside as a dual-threat back under new offensive coordinator Arthur Smith. Target Warren as a high-end flex, with RB2 upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jordan Addison begins the 2024 season looking to build on a promising rookie year, despite some uncertainty surrounding his health and quarterback situation for Minnesota. Addison was effective early last season, averaging 4.5 catches for 60.3 yards per game over the first eight weeks, but his production dropped after Kirk Cousins' injury. With T.J. Hockenson missing time and Sam Darnold now the starting QB, Addison's role could be crucial in the passing game. In Week 1, he faces a Giants defense that allowed the fifth-most fantasy points to wide receivers last season, so the 22-year-old wideout is poised to get off to another hot start.

player.seasonOutlook: Addison had some ups-and-downs in his rookie season. Playing with four different QBs and taking over WR1 responsibilities while Justin Jefferson was out, Addison turned in seven performances with at least 15 fantasy points, third most among rookie wide receivers. Most impressively, his 10 touchdowns were tied for fourth most among all wideouts. Expect those touchdowns to come down with Jefferson fully healthy and Kirk Cousins in Atlanta. While super-talented, Addison is the No. 2 pass-catcher for a journeyman QB at arguably the deepest position in fantasy football, so it's best to view him as a WR4 or WR5 entering draft season.

The Browns finished as the No. 3 D/ST last season (9.8 PPG), while rankings top 10 in sacks and interceptions. This is an aggressive scheme under coordinator Jim Schwartz, one that held opposing offenses to only 4.5 yards per play, lowest in the league. Led by elite pass rusher Myles Garrett, with playmakers Jeremiah Owusu-Koramoah and Denzel Ward on the backend, the Browns should again be an elite fantasy defense in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jake Moody and the 49ers face a tough Jets defense in Week 1, but they are still solid favorites at home. The Jets allowed 19.5 points per game in 2023, which was 12th best in the NFL. Moody converted a league high 60 extra points last season. This gives Moody a solid fantasy floor, but 49ers offense was so efficient it ended up hurting his ceiling last season, as he attempted just 25 field goals, 3rd fewest in the league.  He will look to improve his accuracy in 2024, as well, after missing four of those attempts.

player.seasonOutlook: Moody gained notoriety after converting all 148 extra points at Michigan, eventually becoming the first kicker selected in the 2023 NFL draft. The heir to Robbie Gould's uprights, Moody made good on 21 of 25 field goal attempts (84%) while nailing all but one extra point (60 of 61 attempts) during his rookie campaign. Tied to an elite scoring offense, Moody is capable of posting top-five fantasy numbers at the position.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tyreek Hill looks to pop off for the Dolphins in Week 1 against Jacksonville. Hill is off consecutive 1,700 yard seasons, and averaged 15.1 ypc last season at 29 years old, the second-highest mark of his career. He's scored at least seven touchdowns every year since his rookie campaign, and it wasn't just big plays last year, as Hill had five catches in all but two games and was held below 58 yards once. Jacksonville allowed a moderate 7.1 ypa, but ranked third to last in surrendering catches of 40+ yards a season ago and had the eighth fewest sacks, suggesting time to throw and for Hill to get downfield.

player.seasonOutlook: Hill enters his third season with the Dolphins after another exquisite season, in which he averaged 10.7 targets and 23.5 fantasy points per game. Hill was one of only eight players in the league who had at least 90 receptions and 1,200 receiving yards last season. Targets are among the most predictable year-to-year counting stats for wide receivers, and he remains the top option in a Dolphins offense that ranked second in passing yards in 2023, a trend that's expected to continue. Despite Hill entering his age-30 season, he should still be one of the first receivers selected in fantasy drafts.

outlooksByWeek.1: A.J. Brown topped 100 receptions for the first time in his NFL career last season for the Eagles, while also nearly gaining 1,500 yards for the second-straight year. However, he managed just seven touchdowns and averaged a career-low 13.7 yards per grab. Nevertheless, Brown remains as explosive as ever, and the Philadelphia offense should be even better with Saquon Barkley in the fold at running back.  In Week 1, Brown may face a difficult matchup shadowed by Jaire Alexander of the Packers, though, and Green Bay allowed just 206.8 passing yards per tilt in 2023, which was ninth in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: Brown's second season in Philadelphia statistically mirrored his excellent debut, as he was fifth in receiving yards and provided a cool 17 fantasy points per game, eighth among wide receivers. The way Brown statistically achieved his numbers was a bit disturbing for fantasy managers (and the stumbling Eagles), as he dominated over a six-game stretch early on, averaging 138.5 receiving yards and tallying five touchdowns from Weeks 3 through 8, then reaching 100 yards in just one of the final nine contests. Still, QB Jalen Hurts leads an elite offense, and even with WR DeVonta Smith and new RB Saquon Barkley in the mix, Brown will see ample targets and end zone opportunities. Expect another season as a WR1 option and potential first-round choice.

outlooksByWeek.1: Drake London has looked the part since being drafted by Atlanta in the first round of the 2022 NFL Draft, and his first step to truly breaking out Year 3 will be to dominate in a tough Week 1 matchup against the Steelers. In the first two years of his career London was held back by a run-first offense and some of the NFL's worst QB play, but new quarterback Kirk Cousins will be a tremendous upgrade under center for the Falcons, even if he's somewhat hampered while working his way back from an Achilles tear. New OC Zac Robinson has never called plays before, but if his time with the Rams is any indication, Atlanta's new offense will feature the passing game and three-wide formations more heavily than recent years. London will have a difficult Week 1 matchup if Steelers cornerback Joey Porter shadows him all game, but given how well his skillset aligns with Cousins' preference for targeting the intermediate area of the field, London will still be the favorite to lead the team in targets.

player.seasonOutlook: London is entering his third NFL season well positioned for a big statistical leap after Atlanta's offseason coaching change. Out is Arthur Smith, whose run-heavy scheme limited London to 72-866-4 and 69-905-2 receiving lines during his first two campaigns. The 2022 first-round pick has impressed when utilized, but has yet to finish a season better than 40th among WRs in routes and has 14 career end zone targets to his name. The underwhelming usage figures to change in a big way with Zac Robinson calling plays and Kirk Cousins under center. London is still entering his prime at age-23 and has elite upside in Atlanta's new scheme. He's best-valued as a good WR2, but there's room for more.

outlooksByWeek.1: Nico Collins will begin his season on the road in Week 1 against a Colts defense that ranked in the middle of the pack defending wide receivers last season. He enjoyed a breakout third NFL season with 1,297 yards and eight TDs during the 2023 regular season, including a whopping 341 yards and two TDs in two games against the Colts. The Texans traded for fellow WR Stefon Diggs and Tank Dell is back after breaking his leg last season, but Collins figures to remain a key target for second-year QB C.J. Stroud. Collins will face a similar Colts defense to the one he eviscerated last season, as Indianapolis brought back all 10 players that made double-digit starts on defense in 2023.

player.seasonOutlook: If Year 3 saw Collins break out in a big way, what does his fourth season have in store? It's impressive to note that despite being just 30th in the league in targets last season, Collins finished eighth in receiving yardage. Second only to Tyreek Hill in yards per route run in 2023, Collins shined via both surface and advanced statistics. This was all accomplished during a season that saw him miss multiple games due to injury. Even as the team brought in target competition for this upcoming season in Stefon Diggs, Collins' unique verticality, prime age and established rapport with C.J. Stroud inspires confidence in WR1 expectations for the Texans. You'll likely need to be aggressive in drafts to get your hands on this ascending wideout in the early rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: Patrick Mahomes is coming off what was by his standards a disappointing 2023 regular season, as his 4,183 passing yards and 27 passing touchdowns were his lowest totals since 2019, when he played only 14 games. Kansas City didn't rest on its laurels as back-to-back Super Bowl champions though, working to inject more speed into its receiving corps by signing Marquise Brown and selecting Xavier Worthy with the 28th overall pick in the 2024 Draft. While more downfield threats will be welcome, Mahomes will still have veteran tight end Travis Kelce as his primary target, and second-year wideout Rashee Rice as a yard-after-catch merchant on underneath routes and bubble screens. Mahomes will look to begin a bounce-back campaign in Week 1 against a tough Ravens defense that ranked first in the league in 2023 in yards per attempt allowed, and tied for second in passing touchdowns allowed.

player.seasonOutlook: Though Mahomes' 2023 saw him post his worst yards per attempt (7.0), aDOT (6.2), touchdown (4.5%) and interception (2.3%) rates of his six seasons as an NFL regular, consider the context: He was working with his weakest set of receivers in any of those years. The Chiefs were worst in the league in drops (38) and had the second-worst catch rate on throws 20-plus yards downfield (27.4%), after having been seventh best in that department the season before. Mahomes made it work -- he led the team to a Super Bowl title, after all -- and it's a testament to his overwhelming, Hall of Fame-caliber talent that he finished eighth among quarterbacks in scoring in spite of his supporting cast. The additions of Marquise Brown and Xavier Worthy, coupled with Rashee Rice's late-season emergence, should give Mahomes the weapons necessary to rebound as a top-five positional pick and early-round selection.

outlooksByWeek.1: Dalton Kincaid will look to start a breakout second season for the Bills in Week 1 against the Cardinals. He managed 673 yards and only two touchdowns as a rookie, though produced an impressive 275 yards over the team's final four games - including two during the postseason. Buffalo traded top wideout Stefon Diggs and allowed Gabe Davis to depart via free agency, making Kincaid the team's top returning receiver. He figures to receive sufficient snaps out wide rather than in line as a blocker as Josh Allen works to establish chemistry with his new options. A matchup against a Cardinals defense that conceded the third-most touchdown passes (32) a season ago and has historically been vulnerable to opposing tight ends offers a chance for Kincaid to start quickly.

player.seasonOutlook: What will Kincaid do for an encore after a solid rookie year? He split snaps with Dawson Knox for most of the season, but once Knox was injured, Kincaid showed fantasy managers what he's capable of. From Weeks 8 through 12, Kincaid operated as the starter and led all Bills in targets (37). With both Stefon Diggs and Gabe Davis departing this offseason, Buffalo is lacking a reliable pass-catcher. Kincaid is a candidate to lead the Bills in targets this season, with competition coming from free-agent addition Curtis Samuel and second-round pick Keon Coleman. Kincaid is a midrange TE1 target with elite upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Rhamondre Stevenson looks set for a workhorse role for the Patriots in Week 1 against the Bengals. New England's offense is in transition and will lean on Stevenson for as long as the game remains competitive while QB Jacoby Brissett will be asked to game manage. The offensive line and game script will be a season-long concern, but for at least a half to open the season, Stevenson will get a Bengals run defense that allowed the seventh most rushing yards in 2023 and 4.7 ypa. His use in the passing game is less certain and his rushing volume likely decreases as the game wears on.

player.seasonOutlook: Stevenson enters his fourth season with the Patriots with career averages of 15.1 touches, 74.3 total yards and 12.4 fantasy points per game. While he demonstrated his ability to handle an every-down role in 2022, Stevenson shared the workload with veteran Ezekiel Elliott last season, and missed the final five games due to injury. With new head coach Jerod Mayo succeeding Bill Belichick and the addition of running back Antonio Gibson in the offseason, the Patriots' backfield remains projected as a committee. New England's offense was poor last season, and with a rookie at quarterback, it may not improve much in 2024. Despite Stevenson's expressed desire to be the featured back, he is best viewed as a high-end flex option in fantasy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tank Dell has recovered from a fractured fibula and shouldn't have any limitations in Week 1 against a Colts defense that allowed the fifth-most points per game last season but ranked in the middle of the pack against wide receivers. Prior to getting hurt in Week 13 of his rookie season, Dell set a Texans franchise rookie record with seven receiving TDs and racked up 709 receiving yards. Despite the addition of WR Stefon Diggs via trade and the return of WR Nico Collins, who led the team with 1,297 receiving yards in 2023, Dell is poised to play a prominent role in a Houston passing attack orchestrated by second-year QB C.J. Stroud. Dell had 72 yards and a TD in his only game against the AFC South rival Colts last season.

player.seasonOutlook: If Dell's rookie season saw him set a franchise rookie record for receiving scores in just 11 games, a second season bears real excitement. He is expected to be fully back from a broken fibula that shortened his prolific first season in the league, and Dell also, fortunately, shouldn't be limited by a shooting wound incurred in the offseason. Forging a dynamic duo with C.J. Stroud as one of the most exciting big-play tandems in the NFL, Year 2 could be even more compelling for Dell. Target competition is a real factor on a depth chart that includes Nico Collins and Stefon Diggs, yet, as last season suggests, Dell can do a lot of damage without immense volume. The history of second-year receiving ascension also bodes well for Dell, making him a worthy WR3 target as a key part of a rising offense.

outlooksByWeek.1: Brian Robinson enters the 2024 campaign as the starter at running back for the Commanders, but his grip on the role is far from firm.  Washington added Austin Ekeler via free agency, and Ekeler figures to dominate the pass-catching downs in this new-look offense.  Meanwhile, Jeremy McNichols beat out Chris Rodriguez and could also steal some carries from Robinson, who rushed for 733 yards and four touchdowns a season ago.  Add in the fact that new quarterback Jayden Daniels will also be rushing a lot, and Robinson could struggle.  In Week 1, Washington will face a Tampa Bay defense that excelled against the run in 2023, allowing just 95.3 yards per tilt on the ground, which was fifth in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: Robinson returns as Washington's lead rusher. Robinson started 15 games for the Commanders in 2023, averaging 13.2 fantasy points per game, the same figure as his new backfield competition, veteran Austin Ekeler. One man's emergence can equal another's downfall. Adding Ekeler hardly means Robinson loses all fantasy value, though. At 6-2, 230 pounds, the bruising Robinson may see extensive early down work and cede pass catching responsibilities, offering similar value. Even with Ekeler around, Robinson is talented enough to be a midround sleeper pick and RB3 choice.

outlooksByWeek.1: David Montgomery is entering his second season with the Lions, coming off a strong debut where he rushed for 1,015 yards and 13 touchdowns. While Montgomery was the primary power back in 2023, Jahmyr Gibbs is expected to take on the lead role this year, with Montgomery likely serving as the 1B option in the backfield. Detroit's dominant offensive line should continue to create opportunities for both backs, though Montgomery's receiving work may be limited. In Week 1, Montgomery faces a Rams defense that was stingy against the run last season, allowing only 77.5 rushing yards per game to opposing RBs, ranking 8th in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: Montgomery signed with the Lions in 2023 and quickly put together the most efficient season of his young career. In a committee with Jahmyr Gibbs, Monty was a solid RB2 for fantasy managers, providing a steady dose of rushing yards and touchdowns. Montgomery was ninth in rushing yards, third in rushing touchdowns and handled the third-most carries inside the 5 last season. He lacks passing-game upside (16 catches in 14 games last season), but behind a premier offensive line in Detroit, Montgomery will again be a serviceable RB2 in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Courtland Sutton emerged as a favorite red-zone target for Russell Wilson in 2023, scoring eight of his career-high 10 receiving touchdowns from inside the 20, but the rest of his production in a sluggish Broncos passing game was a disappointment. Wilson is now in Pittsburgh, but Jerry Jeudy is also gone, leaving Sutton as the clear top wideout on the Denver roster. If he establishes chemistry with rookie quarterback Bo Nix quickly, Sutton could reach 1,000 yards for the first time since 2019.  In Week 1, he'll take on a Seahawks secondary that ranked in the bottom half of the league in 2023 in receiving yards and yards per target allowed to wide receivers.

player.seasonOutlook: Following along with what was a team-wide theme, Sutton fell short of expectations again in 2023, marking three consecutive seasons he has failed to crack the positional top 30 in fantasy points despite pacing the Broncos in both routes run and targets. Though his career-best 10 touchdowns were a bright spot, advanced measures deemed it a fortunate total. And since he entered the season with just 14 TDs in 65 career games, it was quite a surprise. Sutton enters his age-29 season working with his ninth different quarterback, and one probably a step down talent-wise from Russell Wilson. Still, the offseason trade of Jerry Jeudy opens up some targets and paves the way for Sutton to be the Broncos' receiving alpha dog. He's best drafted as a WR3 with potential receptions upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Ladd McConkey was never the top option at Georgia during his college career, but he was extremely efficient on the volume he did get, and a strong showing at the Combine convinced the Chargers to select him in the second round of the 2024 Draft. McConkey combines decent size with good speed and elite route-running skills, a combination that could make him the most natural replacement for Keenan Allen as Justin Herbert's top target. Holdover Joshua Palmer and 2023 first-round Quentin Johnston are also competing for positioning on the depth chart, but McConkey appears to have the most upside of the trio. He'll make his NFL debut in Week 1 against a Raiders secondary that finished in the bottom half of the league in 2023 in receiving touchdowns allowed and yards per target allowed to wideouts.

player.seasonOutlook: Though Puka Nacua did it just last season, it's not common historically that a second-day draft pick emerges as his team's go-to receiver. McConkey has a very real chance to do just that, considering the team's aggressive move to trade up for him at No. 34 overall, addressing what was an especially weak spot on the team. He's a polished route-runner who, despite a disappointing and injury-limited senior season at Georgia, excelled at the combine (4.39 40 time), a reminder of his elite speed and quickness. Expect McConkey to get an extended look during the preseason, with a high probability of emerging as Justin Herbert's preferred target before the 2024 season concludes. There's WR3 upside here.

The Jets D/ST finished as the No. 4 D/ST last season, averaging 9.4 points per game. New York's defense was great despite its offensive woes. The team allowed 292.3 total yards per game, the third fewest in the league, and also gave up only 20.9 points per game, which ranked 12th. The Jets will return most of their key defensive players in 2024, including Quincy Williams, C.J. Mosley and Sauce Gardner. Meanwhile, the Jets' offense should be better with Aaron Rodgers back under center, which will keep the defense a bit fresher. This Jets defense should be targeted as one of the top fantasy units.

outlooksByWeek.1: Younghoe Koo, in his sixth season with the Falcons, suit up Week 1 against a Steelers defense that was solid at preventing touchdowns last season, as only five teams allowed fewer points in 2023. Across his time with Atlanta, Koo has never made less than 86.5 percent of his field goals, and the arrival of QB Kirk Cousins should now provide this offense with more consistent scoring opportunities. In each of the last two seasons Koo went 32-of-37 on FGAs in the regular season.

player.seasonOutlook: Koo tied Justin Tucker for eighth in the NFL with 32 field goals made last season for an underwhelming Falcons offense, which kept Koo outside of the top 15 in fantasy points at the position. He remains one of the most accurate kickers in history (88.5%), and the Falcons will have a much different look offensively this season with Raheem Morris as the new head coach and Kirk Cousins starting at quarterback. That should trickle down to Koo, who is a safe bet for a top-12 season and the upside of the top five.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jonathan Taylor is healthy and ready to lead Indianapolis' backfield in Week 1 against a Texans defense that allowed the sixth-fewest rushing yards to running backs in 2023. An ankle injury landed Taylor on the PUP list amid a contract dispute to begin last season, but he produced six touchdowns in his final five appearances last season, which culminated with a 188-yard performance on the ground in a season-ending loss to Houston. Questions still linger about mobile QB Anthony Richardson's proficiency as a passer, so the Colts are expected to lean heavily on the ground game, even against the stout Texans front. Taylor faces minimal competition for backfield touches, as backup Trey Sermon is nursing a hamstring injury and third-stringer Tyler Goodson has just 87 career rushing yards.

player.seasonOutlook: An appraisal of Taylor's four-year career thus far shows his epic, All-Pro 2021 effort as an outlier of sorts. His other three NFL seasons include rushing outcomes between 74.1 and 78.3 yards per game and a total of 24 scores in 36 games, painting a picture of a strong RB1 candidate, just not the RB1 overall. It's worth noting we've yet to see Taylor take handoffs from Anthony Richardson, a reality that presents a blend of mystery and upside ahead of this season. With an unproven collection of backs behind him on the depth chart and the potential for a league-leading touch tally, Taylor remains a worthy early-round fantasy pick, even if that 2021 opus isn't the appropriate expectation.

outlooksByWeek.1: Josh Allen's campaign opens with a seemingly soft Week 1 matchup when the Bills host the Cardinals. Arizona allowed 7.6 YPA last season and 32 touchdown passes while only registering 33 sacks. They didn't do much to address their weaknesses in the offseason, and look particularly vulnerable at cornerback. Allen will have to deal with the loss of top wide receiver Stefon Diggs, though the matchup suggests he'll hit the ground running both figuratively and literally with at least eight rushing touchdowns in all but one season as a pro.

player.seasonOutlook: Allen is back for his seventh season with the Bills. The dual-threat quarterback has been a fantasy dynamo over the past three seasons, averaging 24.7 fantasy points per game (best among QBs). Allen lost Stefon Diggs and Gabe Davis this offseason, which is notable because he averaged only 253.3 passing yards per game last season (his lowest since 2019) and he rushed for his fewest yards since 2020. He more than made up for the rushing decline with 15 rush TDs, which will be tough to repeat. It will be difficult to replace Diggs, but the team did add Curtis Samuel in free agency and Keon Coleman with the No. 33 pick in the draft. Allen is still firmly on the QB1 radar, but managers shouldn't be surprised if we see some regression in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Sam LaPorta, a standout rookie last season, set the new benchmark for receptions by a rookie tight end with 86 catches and added 10 touchdowns. He remains the clear second option in the Lions' passing game behind Amon-Ra St. Brown, and with room for growth in Year 2, LaPorta should continue to be a significant fantasy asset. He appears ready for Week 1 after missing part of training camp due to a hamstring issue. LaPorta has an opportunity to pick up right where he left off last season, facing a Rams defense that allowed eight touchdowns to tight ends last season, tied for 28th in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: LaPorta is back as the Lions' starting tight end after putting together a historic rookie season which saw him finish the season as TE1. LaPorta and Jared Goff immediately hit it off, with the young tight end becoming a trusted target and ranking top five in routes, targets, receptions, receiving yards, touchdowns and end zone targets, as well as finishing second in team target share. Fantasy managers should expect more of the same in 2024 with the Lions returning the majority of their starting offense, LaPorta should be the top tight end off the board on draft day.

outlooksByWeek.1: Stefon Diggs was traded to the Texans in the offseason, and he'll look to make a strong first impression in Week 1 against a Colts defense that ranked in the middle of the pack against wide receivers last season but allowed 24.4 points per game overall, fifth-most in the NFL. Diggs landed in one of the few spots without a significant QB downgrade compared to Josh Allen, as Texans QB C.J. Stroud led the NFL with 273.9 passing yards per game as a rookie last season. The 30-year-old wide receiver faded down the stretch with Buffalo in 2023, as he had only 563 receiving yards in the last 11 regular-season games after racking up 620 yards through Week 6. Nonetheless, Diggs eclipsed the 1,000-yard threshold for a sixth consecutive season.

player.seasonOutlook: A blockbuster spring trade saw Diggs move from Orchard Park to the heart of Texas as he heads into his 10th year in the NFL. The questions are clear: Was Diggs' disappearing act down the stretch last season a sign of steep decline? Or rather a shift in priorities amid a midseason change in Buffalo's offensive coaching leadership? A counter to the demise angle would be Diggs ranking sixth in the NFL in yards per game through Week 9 last season. With motivation to thrive both reputationally and contractually, the potential for a rewarding percentage of C.J. Stroud's attention means fantasy investors can confidently draft Diggs as a WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Deebo Samuel opens the season Week 1 in a tough matchup against a talented Jets secondary that allowed fewer than ten receptions to wide receivers per game in 2023, fewest in the league. The Jets will do well to perform that well against the 49ers this weekend, as coach Kyle Shannahan is never short on ideas to get the ball into Samuel's hands, including giving him over 2 carries per game last season. Samuel is one of the most explosive playmakers in the NFL, averaging 9.0 yards after catch in 2023. Even in a difficult matchup, he is still a solid fantasy option this weekend.
