player.seasonOutlook: The 49ers are flush with talent, making each player's volume difficult to predict on a weekly basis. Christian McCaffrey's arrival, however, appears to have had the biggest impact on Samuel, whose rushing opportunities have dwindled from 3.7 per game in 2021 to 2.5 per contest in 2023. Still, the wideback continued to produce for fantasy managers, thriving in the red area of the field with a team-leading number of red zone looks (17) and 12 total TDs (WR4). While durability is a concern, Samuel's versatile usage and overall efficiency provide him with a sky-high ceiling. Target him as a WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: De'Von Achane will look to catch lightning in a bottle for the Dolphins in Week 1 against Jacksonville. Achane averaged a whopping 7.8 ypc as a rookie, scoring eight times in 11 games. But he also missed six games and tallied double-digit carries just five times while also not factoring much in the passing game, catching 27 balls for a lower ypc than his rushing prowess. Healthy and ready to run, Achane faces a Jaguars defense that ranked ninth in total rushing allowed, but a getable 4.2 ypc and 13 rushes of 20+ yards, the ninth-highest in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: What will Achane do as an encore to his impressive rookie season? He led the league in yards per carry (7.8), among those with a minimum of 100 attempts. The Dolphins were one of the league's most dynamic offenses last season, ranking third in total yards and points per game under head coach and playcaller Mike McDaniel. Expect more of the same in 2024. One red flag with Achane is his durability, as he missed six games last season. However, he remains lethal with the football in his hands, averaging 17.3 fantasy points per game despite only 12.0 touches per game. Those rates scream regression candidate, but that should be offset by a boost in volume in Year 2. Achane will split touches with Raheem Mostert, but he can be drafted as an excellent, high-end flex option with tremendous upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: D'Andre Swift joins the Bears in 2024 with a chance to be the centerpiece of a revamped rushing attack. After a solid season in Philadelphia where he surpassed 1,000 rushing yards for the first time, Swift is poised to thrive in Chicago's improved offense. With a clear path to a three-down role, Swift's versatility should provide a significant boost. However, his ability to handle a full workload remains a question, given his previous injury issues and limited volume. In Week 1, Swift will face a tough Titans run defense that allowed the 6th-fewest fantasy points per game to opposing RBs last year.

player.seasonOutlook: Swift finds himself in Chicago after a one-year stop in Philadelphia. The former pass-catching specialist with the Lions swapped roles when joining the Eagles, ranking 12th in carries and finishing outside the top 20 in targets. It was an odd year for the now-25-year-old running back. It was Swift's most productive season on the ground, yet he lost fantasy value by losing touchdown opportunities to Jalen Hurts and seeing fewer targets in the passing game, culminating in a career-low 12.5 fantasy points per game. Now leading a committee in a lower volume offense, Swift can be relied upon as a dual-threat option for the Bears and a top-25 RB for fantasy managers.

outlooksByWeek.1: Kyle Pitts and the Falcons, led by new quarterback Kirk Cousins, open the season with a Week 1 matchup against the Steelers defense, which ranked sixth in the NFL last season. Now two quiet years removed from his 1,000-yard rookie season, but no longer having to deal with injury, a run-first offense, and some of the league's worst QB play, Pitts is in solid position to truly live up to his draft capital as a former No. 4 overall pick. Still just heading into his age-24 season, Pitts should benefit from an Atlanta offense ready to funnel through himself, WR Drake London and RB Bijan Robinson as its top options. London could be shadowed by Pittsburgh's top CB Joey Porter in Week 1, in which case Pitts will be in prime position to immediately demonstrate chemistry with Cousins and take advantage of matchup mismatches.

player.seasonOutlook: Perhaps no player has been more frustrating to roster in fantasy over the past three seasons than Pitts, as the Falcons and coach Arthur Smith constantly mismanaged his massive talent level while trying to reinvent the wheel. Pitts has just 149 catches for six touchdowns in his three seasons, but things are looking up. Raheem Morris takes over for Smith, Kirk Cousins takes over for Desmond Ridder at QB, and the Falcons suddenly have a potent passing blueprint. If the Falcons make Pitts a priority and get him the ball, his talent should take care of everything else. Despite the early struggles, Pitts will be drafted as a TE1 and should come in hungry, looking to make up for lost time.

outlooksByWeek.1: Justin Tucker heads into the 2024 season as Baltimore's kicker for the 13th straight season. He's dipped below a 90 percent accuracy rate on field goals for two consecutive seasons but still remains one of the best kickers in the league heading into a Week 1 matchup against the Chiefs. Kansas City had an elite defense in 2023 and returns many of its key players, though the secondary has turned over some key positions, meaning Baltimore could have success moving the ball and getting Tucker into field-goal range. Barring weather concerns, he should be a startable kicker  in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: One of the league's most consistent placekickers, with the leg strength to drive the ball on deeper attempts, Tucker logged 155 fantasy points last season (second most in the league), while converting on 86.5% of field goals and hitting 98.1% of his extra point attempts. Surprisingly, Tucker struggled from 50-plus yards in 2023, converting just one of five attempts. Given his track record, however, plus the opportunities he will get from Baltimore's prolific offense, Tucker remains a top-five fantasy kicker.

While not as staunch as in previous years, the 49ers D/ST remained a formidable unit in 2023, tallying 48 sacks, 22 INTs and allowing the fourth-fewest completions of 40+ yards (five). San Francisco's defensive line experienced a good amount of turnover this offseason, losing Arik Armstead, Chase Young and Javon Kinlaw, while adding Leonard Floyd, Yetur Gross-Matos and Maliek Collins. The team also addressed the secondary via the draft, adding DBs in the second and fourth rounds. As such, San Francisco figures to remain a top-five D/ST, flirting with double-digit fantasy points on a weekly basis.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jayden Reed enters his sophomore season looking to build upon a strong rookie campaign. Last year, Reed led the Packers with 64 receptions, 793 receiving yards, and 10 total touchdowns. He aims to maintain his role as Green Bay's top receiving option, but consistent target share remains a concern with competition from Romeo Doubs, Christian Watson, and Dontayvion Wicks. In Week 1, Reed faces an Eagles defense that allowed the most fantasy points per game to opposing wide receivers in 2023, presenting a great opportunity for him to assert himself as the primary pass-catcher.

player.seasonOutlook: Reed impressed as a rookie and is back to do it again in his second season with the Packers. The former second-round pick showcased his talent down the stretch with at least 15 fantasy points in seven of his final eight games. In fact, over that stretch, Reed was WR10! The upside is obvious, the only problem is the number of options Jordan Love has at his disposal. Christian Watson is a potential star when healthy, Romeo Doubs has shown his knack for the end zone and Dontayvion Wicks even flashed last season. It's just a deep WR room and it's the deepest position in fantasy. Because of that, Reed checks in as a flex with WR3 upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Austin Ekeler had a borderline catastrophic 2023 campaign with the Chargers, but the hope is that a new squad will rejuvenate the formerly elite running back.  Brian Robinson is technically the starter, and Jeremy McNichols may also see his fair share of touches, but Ekeler should dominate the passing downs as a receiver out of the backfield.  New quarterback Jayden Daniels will vulture plenty of touchdowns from the running backs this season, so Ekeler's value will likely be tied to his abilities as a receiver, as well as health.  In Week 1, Washington will face a Tampa Bay defense that excelled against the run in 2023, allowing just 95.3 yards per tilt on the ground, which was fifth in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: Ekeler signed with the Commanders after a thoroughly disappointing final season with the Chargers. He scored 38 touchdowns during the 2021 and 2022 seasons, which earned him much fantasy love and the top running back spot in many fantasy leagues, but his 2023 was a struggle. Ekeler suffered a high-ankle sprain in Week 1 (while scoring 26.4 PPR points!), missed three games and never really returned to prominence, seeing sketchy volume among his inefficiency. He recorded five top-10 weekly finishes at RB in 14 games. Ekeler will not cost a first-round pick this season, not in Washington's moribund offense, but if health and volume return, there is enticing bounce-back possibility as a TD-driven, RB2 choice.

outlooksByWeek.1: Brian Thomas will make his NFL debut in Week 1 against a Miami secondary that allowed the sixth-most touchdowns to wide receivers last season (17). The 23rd overall pick in the 2024 NFL Draft out of LSU will look to beat out Parker Washington for a role in three-receiver sets alongside Christian Kirk and offseason addition Gabe Davis in a Jacksonville receiving corps that lost Calvin Ridley and Zay Jones to free agency. Kirk hurt his calf in August but is expected to play. Miami replaced Xavien Howard with Kendall Fuller in the outside cornerback spot opposite Jalen Ramsey.

player.seasonOutlook: Selecting Thomas in the first round highlights the Jaguars' clear agenda this offseason to provide Trevor Lawrence with an upgraded collection of downfield playmakers. Overshadowed to a degree by LSU teammate Malik Nabers' prolific prospect profile, Thomas established quite the collegiate career of his own. After all, his 12 touchdown hauls on passes of at least 20 yards downfield last season marks the most by any FBS player in a season since ESPN Stats & Information began tracking air yards in 2011. Lawrence, meanwhile, is third in the NFL in passes of least 10 air yards since the start of the 2022 campaign. The rare rookie from this class with a projection for a triple-digit target workload, taking Thomas in the late-middle rounds of your draft could prove profitable.

outlooksByWeek.1: Keon Coleman will make his debut for the Bills in Week 1 against the Cardinals. After losing Stefon Diggs and Gabe Davis during the offseason, Buffalo used a second-round selection on the rookie from Florida State to reset their receiving corps. Coleman offers elite size at 6-foot-4 and could become an immediate red zone weapon after scoring 11 times last season against an Arizona defense that allowed 32 touchdown passes in 2023 and vulnerable at cornerback. But as with most rookie wide receivers, there's an acclimation process and Coleman didn't show much this preseason. And his opening snap and target count likely won't be a season-high.

player.seasonOutlook: Coleman was selected by Buffalo in the second round of April's draft and is immediately tethered to one of the league's best quarterbacks in Josh Allen. Coleman easily could pace the Bills in targets out of the gate after Stefon Diggs and Gabe Davis left this offseason. The rookie out of Florida State led the Seminoles in receptions, yards and touchdowns in his final collegiate season. With his downfield prowess and red zone potential, Coleman should be on your radar in the middle rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: Breece Hall enters Week 1 as a clear workhorse for the Jets as they prepare to face the 49ers on Monday night. Hall closed 2023 with 70 carries across his final three games, while catching an impressive 76 balls during his sophomore campaign. It's a challenging matchup, as San Francisco allowed the third fewest rushing yards and fourth fewest rushing touchdowns a season ago, but his volume shouldn't be questioned. Far from a smash situation, Hall is positioned to enjoy a heavy workload that can lead to upside.

player.seasonOutlook: Hall appeared fully recovered from his ACL tear by the end of the 2023 season. He was one of the few bright spots in a struggling Jets offense that was without future Hall of Fame quarterback Aaron Rodgers. From Week 5 on, Hall was no longer on a snap count and his usage increased significantly, as he averaged 20.5 touches and 20.2 fantasy points per game over the final 13 games. Despite the Jets' offense ranking 29th in run block win rate, Hall consistently produced and also led all running backs in targets, receptions and receiving yards. Hall's potential is even greater with Rodgers hopefully under center for the entire 2024 season. Fantasy managers should feel confident drafting him as the second running back off the board, behind Christian McCaffrey.

outlooksByWeek.1: Chris Olave's hopes of finally emerging as a true alpha wide receiver for the Saints will be put to the test early, with a tough matchup against Carolina's secondary on deck Week 1. The Panthers allowed just 11 touchdowns to the WR position last season, and when top CB Jaycee Horn shadowed Olave in Week 14 last season, he was limited to just four catches for 28 yards on five targets, but salvaged his day with a touchdown. Still, Olave has started his career with back-to-back 1,000-yard seasons, and all he could need for a Year 3 breakout is modest improvement of his own, plus another offseason to have built chemistry with QB Derek Carr. Fellow wideouts Rashid Shaheed and A.T. Perry are most comfortable as deep threats, so if this offense wants to do more than regularly dump off to RB Alvin Kamara, the passing game will have to consistently go through Olave.

player.seasonOutlook: Olave is entering his third NFL season after posting a pair of top-25 fantasy campaigns in his his first two campaigns. The 24 year old saw a boost in targets, receptions, yardage and touchdowns in his second season, finishing top 20 among receivers in all but the latter category. The Saints didn't add any significant target competition for Olave, which means he's a near lock to continue handling a massive workload. More usage near the goal line would get Olave to the next level (14 career end zone targets), but he's a good bet for another 80-catch, 1,000-plus yard season and thus makes for a fringe WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Marvin Harrison will make his debut for the Cardinals in Week 1 at Buffalo, who were the NFL's sixth best passing defense last year. Harrison is one of the most highly-rated wide receiver prospects ever, and he projects to immediately become Kyler Murray's number one receiving option. He should see plenty of targets in this game, especially if the talented Buffalo offense forces the Cardinals to throw more frequently in a negative game script. Harrison will have a tough task on his hands in his first start facing coverage from talented Bills cornerback duo Taron Johnson and Rasul Douglas. The Bills defense had 16 interceptions and held opponents under 220 receiving yards per game last season.

player.seasonOutlook: A polished playmaker with elite NFL bloodlines, Harrison is arguably the most pro-ready player in this year's draft class, regardless of position. Kyler Murray may not be the most consistent passer in the NFL, but he has proven capable of supporting a top-15 fantasy producer at the position (DeAndre Hopkins was a top-15 WR in fantasy PPG in all three of his seasons as a Cardinal). Harrison should easily emerge as Murray's primary option, likely flirting with double-digit targets on a regular basis and making him a priority rookie in redraft and dynasty formats.

outlooksByWeek.1: George Kittle enters his eighth season at tight end for the 49ers against the Jets in Week 1. The Jets have a very good passing defense that ranked third in the NFL last season. The 49ers might need to rely on Kittle to get open in the middle of the field with Deebo Samuel and Brandon Aiyuk dealing with difficult matchups against the talented Jets cornerbacks. There is some cause for optimism for the matchup for Kittle, since the Jets showed some vulnerability to tight ends in 2023, allowing eight receiving touchdowns to the position, tied for second most in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: Despite experiencing a dip in overall efficiency, Kittle buoyed his fantasy stock by scoring 11 TDs in 2022. A regression was, therefore, anticipated heading into 2023. Kittle's TDs did, in fact, decline (with three of his six scores occurring in Week 5), but the 30-year-old still posted a top-five positional fantasy finish, recording a career high in yards per target (11.3) and yards per reception (15.7), both best among TEs. While Kittle was second on the team in targets (behind Brandon Aiyuk), his week-to-week volume fluctuated, presenting a frustrating conundrum for fantasy managers. Kittle's do-it-all skill set combined with the depth of pass-catchers in the 49ers' offense figures to lead to boom-or-bust play again in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Joe Mixon is set to lead Houston's backfield in Week 1 against a Colts defense that allowed the fifth-most fantasy points to running backs in 2023. The Colts struggled in every facet of defending RBs, allowing the sixth-most rushing yards (1,767), third-most rushing TDs (16) and fourth-most receiving yards (723) to the position. Mixon signed a three-year, $25.5 million contract in March to replace Devin Singletary atop the depth chart. The 28-year-old Mixon exceeded 1,000 rushing yards in four of seven seasons with the Bengals, including a 1,034-yard campaign on the ground in 2023.

player.seasonOutlook: After joining the Texans in March via trade, Mixon looks to bring his volume-driven, veteran appeal to an emergent Houston offense. While efficiency wasn't the hallmark of Mixon's final season with the Bengals, he did handle a massive workload en route to finishing sixth in total fantasy points among backs and ninth in per-game production in 2023. The Texans didn't pepper the backfield with many targets last season (28th in the league), but the team did rank 12th in both total carries and red zone totes allocated to backs. Without much competition for snaps, targets or touches present on the depth chart, Mixon is poised for another big role on a team flush with receiving weapons that could yield light opposing boxes.

outlooksByWeek.1: Zay Flowers enjoyed a solid rookie season with the Ravens, during which he averaged 53.5 receiving yards and 12.9 fantasy points per game, and he'll begin the 2024 campaign with a Week 1 matchup against Kansas City. Based on last year's results, this would be a tough matchup, as the Chiefs allowed the second-fewest fantasy points per game to opposing wide receivers. However, they were forced to part ways with standout corner L'Jarius Sneed this offseason, whose likely duty in this game would have been to shadow Flowers. Other factors in this game also suggest that Flowers could perform well, as Baltimore will likely need to be aggressive on offense due to a matchup against Patrick Mahomes.

player.seasonOutlook: Flowers kicks off his second pro season after averaging 12.8 PPG in his rookie year, with four games of 19 or more points. He's an explosive mover, with electric ability in space, as 45.1% of his receving yards came after the catch. In Baltimore's system, Flowers can be schemed on screens and manufactured touches, in addition to his multi-level route-running ability. With Flowers expected to see No. 1 volume this season, he should be drafted as a flex/WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jordan Love aims to build on his breakout 2023 campaign as the Packers travel to SAo Paulo, Brazil for a Week 1 matchup against an Eagles defense that ranked 31st in the NFL last year. Love threw for 4,159 yards and 32 touchdowns in his first full season as Green Bay's QB. With dynamic targets like Jayden Reed, Christian Watson, Romeo Doubs and Dontayvion Wicks, Love and head coach Matt LaFleur have plenty of options in their passing attack. Although Philadelphia brought in defensive guru Vic Fangio as their new defensive coordinator in the offseason, expect Love to take advantage of an Eagles secondary that allowed 35 TD passes last season, 31st in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: Love returns as Green Bay's quarterback after leading the Packers to the playoffs as a first-year starter in 2023. While expectations were low considering his limited NFL action and young supporting cast, Love proved doubters wrong by finishing as fantasy's QB7. That includes six top-10 finishes in his final eight games. Love was eighth or better in passing yards, attempts, completions and aDOT, while also finishing second in passing touchdowns and posting a 3-to-1 TD/INT ratio. Love could use his legs a little more, but with his success in 2023 and all of his exciting, young pass-catchers returning, Love should be viewed as a fringe QB1 in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Terry McLaurin is coming off his fourth-straight 1,000-yard season for the Commanders, and should benefit from improved play at the quarterback position in 2024.  That's because Washington drafted Heisman Trophy winner Jayden Daniels with the No. 2 overall pick.  McLaurin also has absolutely no competition for targets, as both Curtis Sauel and Jahan Dotson are no longer with the squad.  McLaurin's ceiling certainly appears higher in 2024, and in Week 1 he will face a Tampa Bay defense that struggled against the pass in 2023, allowing 248.9 passing yards per clash, which was 29th in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: McLaurin's fifth NFL season looked quite a bit like his prior ones, as he crossed 1,000 receiving yards for the fourth consecutive campaign, quite the feat considering Washington's quarterback play during his career. This is a new era, with Jayden Daniels at quarterback, and that helps everyone. The consistent McLaurin has caught between 77 and 87 passes each of the past four seasons, and he has scored four or more touchdowns each season. What looked different in 2023 was how McLaurin got those numbers, with a career-worst 7.6 yards per target and 12.7 yards per reception. Fantasy managers can no longer comfortably choose the durable McLaurin as a WR2, as 27 wide receivers scored more fantasy points last season, but he isn't far from that range, either.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jake Ferguson is coming off of a breakout season for the Cowboys.  Ferguson caught 71 passes for 761 yards and five touchdowns in 2023, operating as a consistent safety valve for quarterback Dak Prescott.  With uncertainty surrounding the wide receivers other than CeeDee Lamb, as well as a potentially lackluster running game, Ferguson should continue to be targeted early and often by Prescott.  Unfortunately, Week 1 provides a rather difficult matchup for the Dallas passing game, as Cleveland allowed the fewest passing yards in the NFL in 2023.

player.seasonOutlook: Ferguson broke out in his second NFL season, ranking ninth among tight ends in receptions and eighth in receiving yards. Only six tight ends caught more than his five touchdowns, and Ferguson closed well with a three-TD outing in the team's wild card playoff loss to the Packers. He benefited from the offseason departure of Dalton Schultz to Houston, then he outproduced Schultz. Cowboys QB Dak Prescott throws a ton of passes, and he looks Ferguson's way quite a bit at the goal line. This is a top-10 fantasy tight end, with upside for the top five.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jaxon Smith-Njigba opens the season third on the Seahawks wide receiver depth chart after a disappointing rookie campaign. In Week 1, he gets to go up against a Denver defense that was ninth worst in the league against the pass last season and didn't make many moves to improve their personnel. While there should be plenty of receiving opportunities in the Seahawks' offense with offensive coordinator Ryan Grubb expected to install an innovative passing game, Smith-Njigba will have to compete with Tyler Lockett and DK Metcalf for targets. It's difficult to trust Smith-Njigba in the opening game against Denver, but there is potential for him to earn a bigger role as the season progresses.

player.seasonOutlook: Eventually finding his footing as the Seahawks' No. 3 WR, Smith-Njigba was largely deployed via the slot as a rookie (64.3% rate) working as a complement to DK Metcalf and Tyler Lockett, both of whom finished inside the top 25 fantasy players at the position. Smith-Njigba is a smooth and reliable receiver who uses agility and crisp routes to gain separation, and at just 22 years old he figures to eventually grow into a starring role. With Lockett and Noah Fant returning, however, targets may be hard to come by in 2024. Seattle's new coaching regime figures to shake things up from a scheme perspective, but how many opportunities they'll immediately grant Smith-Njigba remains to be seen. An injury to the 31-year-old Lockett would pave the way for a potential JSN breakout, who presents with plenty of theoretical upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jayden Daniels has been handed the keys to the offense for Washington as a rookie.  The Heisman Trophy winner is an elite athlete and can torment the opposition with both his legs as well as his arm.  Certainly a learning curve for the rookie is possible, but expectations are extremely high, and the buzz surrounding Daniels this preseason is that he has the look and feel of a future star.  In Week 1, Daniels will face a Buccaneers defense that struggled against the pass in 2023, but excelled against the run, meaning Daniels could be forced to play the role of a pocket passer in his NFL debut.

player.seasonOutlook: Daniels was selected second overall by the Commanders in April's draft, and he may be more valuable in fantasy than the quarterback who went first (Caleb Williams), thanks to his elite running ability. Daniels not only compiled 10 times as many touchdown passes as interceptions while winning the Heisman Trophy in 2023, he also rushed for more than 1,100 yards and 10 more scores. Washington is a good landing spot for Daniels, with savant Kliff Kingsbury directing the offense and ample offensive options around him. Daniels probably slips outside the QB1 options on draft day, but he may end up there by season's end.

outlooksByWeek.1: Chubba Hubbard will start Week 1 against the Saints as the Panthers' top backfield option, and remain so at least until rookie second-round pick Jonathon Brooks completes his rehab from a torn ACL suffered last November. Last season Hubbard overthrew the more expensive Miles Sanders and averaged  19.1 carries and 2.3 catches for 87.0 total yards over Carolina's final seven games. Now on the final year of his rookie deal, Hubbard should begin the season as a workhorse, but Week 1 he'll have a tough matchup against a New Orleans defense that finished eight in points allowed and 13th in yardage last year.  Miles Sander could still have a role off the bench, but given the respective production last season, Hubbard should be considered the favorite to lead Carolina's backfield vs. the Saints.

player.seasonOutlook: Hubbard replaced Miles Sanders as the feature back for the worst offensive team in the league last season, finishing with 902 rush yards and five touchdowns. However, he wasn't exactly efficient in doing so, ranking in the 30s in explosive-run rate, forced missed tackles and yards after contact. Add in the fact that things are still a bit cloudy in Carolina with new head coach Dave Canales, along with the fact they drafted Jonathon Brooks with the 46th pick in the draft, and it's not hard to see Hubbard's fantasy value taking a hit. He is worth a midround pick, as he is expected to be the lead back for at least the first four weeks of the season, while Brooks (ACL recovery) begins the season on IR.

outlooksByWeek.1: Harrison Butker is coming off the most accurate season of his career, and his 33 made field goals was his highest total since 2019. Kansas City's offense took a step back last year but still provided its kicker with plenty of opportunities, and his 137 points put him fourth in the league. The offense appears set to rebound with first-round pick Xavier Worthy and free agent Marquise Brown bolstering the wide receiver corps for Patrick Mahomes, but trading field goals for extra points won't help Butker's overall production. Any scoring chances could be at a premium in Week 1 against a Ravens defense that allowed the fewest points in the league in 2023 at 16.5 per game.

player.seasonOutlook: After missing four games due to an ankle injury in 2022 and posting his worst field goal accuracy numbers of his NFL career, Butker rebounded in a big way for the eventual Super Bowl champions. He set a personal best with his 94.3% field goal success rate, and was a perfect 12-for-12 on his attempts of 40 yards or greater. Butker returns as the placekicker for one of the game's most potent offenses, a prerequisite for the position, which makes him one of the top options in the draft.

The Lions' defense flashed at times during the 2023 season, showcasing some of their top young talent, but ultimately failed to finish inside the top 20. Part of that was their inability to generate sacks, ranking fourth in QB pressures but 23rd in sacks. The most glaring problem was their secondary, giving up the sixth-most yards and passing touchdowns and second-most yards per pass attempt. They added Carlton Davis III in a trade with the Bucs and drafted two top-tier CBs in Terrion Arnold (Alabama) and Ennis Rakestraw Jr. (Missouri). That shores up a major hole and makes the Lions an attractive top 15 fantasy defense in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Amon-Ra St. Brown has seen his production rise steadily each season since being drafted in 2021, setting career highs in catches, yards, targets, and touchdowns last year. He accounted for nearly 30 percent of the Lions' targets in 2023, finishing in the top-five league-wide in each category. With star rookie TE Sam LaPorta and other receivers in the mix, St. Brown remains the primary pass-catching option, excelling in both short-area and yards-after-catch situations. He faces a Rams defense in Week 1 that allowed 246.8 passing yards per game last season, ranking 20th in the NFL. St. Brown's significant target share and consistent performance make him an elite fantasy option each week, regardless of the matchup.

player.seasonOutlook: After inking a new 4-year contract this offseason, St. Brown returns as the leader of the Lions' receiving corps. One of most consistent wide receivers in fantasy, ARSB had an outstanding 11 games with at least 18 fantasy points in 2023. No wide receiver had more top-20 weekly finishes and only Tyreek Hill had more weeks finishing seventh or better. Possessing both a high floor and ceiling, St. Brown was top five in every major receiving category last season and returns to an offense that looks to be just as potent this season. St. Brown is showing no signs of slowing down, and is poised to be a top-five fantasy wide receiver in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jalen Hurts is coming off career-bests of 23 touchdown passes and 15 touchdown runs in 2023 for the Eagles.  However, he also turned the ball over 19 times, 15 of which came via the interception.  Hurts has yet another weapon to lean on in the form of Saquon Barkley, so while Hurts could lose a couple of touchdowns on the ground, he should benefit overall from the presence of another playmaker on offense.  In Week 1, Hurts will face a Green Bay defense that was better against the pass than the run in 2023.

player.seasonOutlook: Hurts comes off his best NFL season, thanks mainly to 15 rushing touchdowns, tying Josh Allen for the most among QBs. In fact, no other QBs reached seven rushing scores. Hurts finished behind only Allen in fantasy points at the position despite playing the final months with a knee injury, as the Eagles collapsed down the stretch. Don't blame Hurts. He averaged 21.5 fantasy points from Weeks 15 through 17, before sitting most of the finale. The Eagles lost C Jason Kelce, but the offensive line and wide receiver options remain top-notch, and the controversial "tush push" play Hurts feasts on remains legal. Expect another fantastic statistical season, and a legitimate chance to finish as fantasy's top scorer.

outlooksByWeek.1: Travis Etienne is set to reprise his three-down role as the top option in Jacksonville's backfield heading into a Week 1 road matchup against a Miami defense that allowed the fifth-fewest rushing yards to RBs in 2023. The 2021 first-round pick missed his rookie season due to injury, then churned out 1,441 scrimmage yards in 2022 and 1,484 scrimmage yards in 2023. The Jaguars opted not to add to the backup options behind Etienne in the offseason, bringing back Tank Bigsby and D'Ernest Johnson. Miami's defense could have a tough time replicating last year's success against the run after an offseason exodus of talent, including DT Christian Wilkins and LB Jerome Baker, who combined for at least 143 tackles each of the past five seasons.

player.seasonOutlook: Fresh off a career campaign that saw him tally the third-most touches in the league, Etienne is firmly in the RB1 discussion as he enters his fourth season. Volume was arguably his greatest asset, as the Clemson product's efficiency has room for improvement (he finished 38th in yards per touch among backs with at least 50 rushing attempts). Etienne is likely to handle another compelling blend of early-down, red zone and receiving opportunities this season. Given such heavy usage, age and production, Etienne's path to repeating a top-12 fantasy finish appears viable.

outlooksByWeek.1: Derrick Henry will make one of the most anticipated debuts of the 2024 season after leaving the Titans to join forces with Lamar Jackson in Baltimore. He'll draw a tough test in Week 1 against Kansas City, a defensive unit that allowed an exactly average number of rushing yards per game (113.0) but also limited opponents to just 0.6 rushing touchdowns per game last season. Nevertheless, Henry should be up to the task. Despite a down season relative to his own lofty standards, he still managed 12 touchdowns while posting 1,381 total yards in 2023. Henry should be in line for a massive workload and will be the top option at the goal line, keeping him in the conversation as an elite fantasy contributor.

player.seasonOutlook: After playing eight seasons in Tennessee, Henry signed with the Ravens in free agency to take over the lead role in the Baltimore backfield. While Henry will turn 30 years old this season, he can still get on a north/south track as a downhill hammer in the run game, with enough juice to create big plays. In 2023, Henry's 272 carries tied for the league lead, and his 2.22 yards after first contact ranked at the top. With the Ravens, Henry will work behind a stronger offensive front and pair with Lamar Jackson to create a dynamic backfield attack. Henry won't give you high-end receving numbers (27 receptions last season), but the rushing volume and scoring opportunities place the veteran in the upper-tier RB2 discussion.

outlooksByWeek.1: Josh Jacobs joins the Packers after a disappointing season with the Raiders, where he rushed for a career-low 805 yards and six touchdowns. His dip in production was due to a combination of lackluster quarterback play, questionable coaching decisions, and missing the final four games of the season due to injury. However, the 26-year-old is only two years removed from leading the NFL with 1,653 rushing yards in 2022 and is expected to serve as a workhorse back in a more formidable Green Bay offense. In Week 1, Jacobs faces a Philadelphia defense that ranked 10th against the run in 2023, allowing 103.4 rushing yards per game.

player.seasonOutlook: Jacobs joins the Packers after spending his first five years with the Raiders. In 2023, Jacobs resumed his go-to-back role and finished second in touches per game. However, despite that volume, Jacobs was RB17 in fantasy points per game, due to career lows in rushing yards, touchdowns and yards per rush. At 26 years old, Jacobs reprises his lead-back duties in Green Bay, replacing Aaron Jones and sharing the backfield with rookie MarShawn Lloyd. Jacobs is one of only five RBs with at least 50 targets in each of the past three seasons, and he gets enough passing-game work to maintain a high weekly floor. With another heavy workload on the horizon, Jacobs is a top-15 running back.

outlooksByWeek.1: Cooper Kupp has a good match-up as the Rams face off against  the Lions defense in Week 1. The Lions had one of the worst pass defenses in the league last year, allowing more than 250 receiving yards per game. They addressed their weak secondary this offseason with several signings. According to reports out of training camp, Kupp is healthier than he was at any point during last year's disappointing season. Kupp has a solid fantasy floor and the ceiling to deliver big fantasy numbers if the game turns into a shootout.

player.seasonOutlook: It was an up-and-down effort from Kupp in 2023, who missed the first four weeks with a hamstring issue and has now missed 13 games the past two seasons. On the plus side, Kupp posted four 100-yard efforts and five outings of 15 or more fantasy points. Unfortunately, he was also held below 40 yards in six of 12 contests, managing single-digit fantasy points in five of those games. Kupp's nose for the end zone saved fantasy managers, as the 30-year-old scored four times from Weeks 13 through 17. Obviously, Puka Nacua's emergence negatively affected Kupp's volume, though the vet remained Matthew Stafford's favorite high-value target. Kupp led the team in red zone opportunities (19, WR9). While he appears past peak value, Kupp's savvy and chemistry with Stafford are solid enough for him to deliver low-end WR2 numbers in PPR formats.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tee Higgins was plagued by injury and subpar quarterback play throughout 2023, though neither of those factors appear to be an issue heading into a Week 1 matchup against New England. Higgins has been overshadowed by Ja'Marr Chase in Cincinnati for the last few seasons, but he still has surpassed 1,000 yards in half of his four campaigns. His potential for Week 1 is particularly intriguing due to the status of Chase, who has held out for a new contract throughout training camp and has yet to take the practice field heading into the season opener. That could leave Higgins as Joe Burrow's top pass-catching option, putting him in line for a potentially big start to the new campaign.

player.seasonOutlook: Higgins is back -- on the franchise tag -- for his fifth pro season with the Bengals. In 12 games played last season, Higgins averaged 11.5 fantasy PPG, but was inconsistent, scoring 22 or more points three times but below 10 points on seven occasions. Higgins will remain unpredictable at times as the secondary target behind Ja'Marr Chase, but he has ability to win on the boundary or as a seam stretcher from the slot. Having a healthy Joe Burrow back on the field for this high-powered offense puts Higgins in the mid-tier flex range, with WR2 upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: David Njoku enjoyed a breakout 2023 season with the Browns, though much of that production came in the second half of the season with Joe Flacco under center. Now, he'll head into a Week 1 matchup against the Cowboys with Deshaun Watson under center, whom Njoku has yet to prove rapport with. Njoku will also deal with additional target competition from Jerry Jeudy, a new addition to Cleveland's receiving corps. That leaves plenty of unknowns to begin the season, though the Cowboys did allow six touchdowns to opposing tight ends in 2023 - a mark more than the league average.

player.seasonOutlook: Njoku, who is entering his eighth season, hit career highs in receptions, receving yards and touchdowns in 2023. He was a fantasy playoff star in Weeks 14-17 with Joe Flacco at quarterback, posting two games of 26 or more points, with at least one touchdown reception in three of four games. On the flip side, Njoku produced three games of double-digit fantasy production, and just one touchdown, in Deshaun Watson's six starts last season. While that can create some concern, we are trusting the rare talent with Njoku as a mid-tier TE1 in Kevin Stefanski's heavily schemed pass game.

outlooksByWeek.1: Javonte Williams struggled last season, his first year back from a serious knee injury that limited him to just four games and 47 carries in 2022. The 35th overall pick in the 2021 Draft, Williams showed his upside as a rookie with 1,219 scrimmage yards and 4.4 yards per carry over 17 contests, but the latter number fell to 3.6 yards per carry in 2023. He was flashing his pre-injury power and burst in training camp this summer, and Denver coach Sean Payton showed his confidence in Williams as a three-down option by letting veteran receiving back Samaje Perine go on cut-down day. Williams should see a significant workload in Week 1 against a Seahawks defense that gave up 4.6 yards per carry and 24 rushing touchdowns in 2023, putting it in the bottom six in the league in both categories.

player.seasonOutlook: Though Williams' numbers were lackluster -- his yards per carry, explosive-play and yards after contact numbers were down considerably compared to pre-knee reconstruction -- credit him for quickly returning to action. He proved ready to play in Week 1, 343 days after tearing the ACL, LCL and posterolateral corner in his right knee, and appeared in 16 games, including handling 15-plus touches nine times. That aggressive recovery, coupled with the hefty workload, might have contributed to the so-so numbers, and he wouldn't be the first player to take a bigger step forward the second year following such a significant operation. Williams, now 24, has a fantasy RB2 ceiling, but he would be wisely selected as a flex while his team overhauls the quarterback position.

outlooksByWeek.1: DeAndre Hopkins is recovering from a knee injury, but he's on track to suit up in Week 1 against a Bears defense that allowed the sixth-most touchdowns to wide receivers in 2023 but limited the position to the ninth-fewest receiving yards. The 32-year-old wide receiver got off to a slow start last season but enjoyed a resurgence after the Titans inserted Will Levis under center in Week 8, as all seven of Hopkins' touchdowns came from that point onward, and six of them were thrown by Levis. Offseason WR additions Calvin Ridley and Tyler Boyd will likely cut into Hopkins' target share, but they will also draw attention from a Bears secondary that brought back its top three cornerbacks from 2023, including Jaylon Johnson.

player.seasonOutlook: Hopkins is entering his 12th NFL season, but he hasn't shown serious signs of aging just yet. Last season, Hopkins posted his highest yards per catch since his first All-Pro effort in 2017. The days of triple-digit reception totals are likely in the past, but a concentrated Titans offense could still afford him well over 100 targets working with a big-armed second-year QB in Will Levis. There is always a degree of risk investing in a receiver in his age-32 season, although it's reasonable to note Hopkins wins at the catch point with a mixture of guile and hands that remains rare at the position. Given the track record, don't be surprised by another solid WR2 showing found at WR3 pricing, though note that Hopkins is expected to miss the first few games of the season due to injury.

outlooksByWeek.1: Trevor Lawrence and the Jaguars open the 2024 season with a Week 1 road matchup against a Dolphins defense that finished in the middle of the pack last season. We could be in for a warm-weather Week 1 shootout in Miami, as the Dolphins will be adjusting to numerous key offseason personnel losses, including CB Xavien Howard, DT Christian Wilkins, LB Jerome Baker and S Brandon Jones. Jacksonville's offense also made some personnel changes, replacing WRs Calvin Ridley and Zay Jones with 23rd overall draft pick Brian Thomas and free-agent signing Gabe Davis. Christian Kirk is back after missing the last five games of 2023 due to a groin injury, though the dependable WR is nursing a calf injury heading into the season opener. RB Travis Etienne and TE Evan Engram are also returning after combining for 172 catches last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Even as we enter the fourth season of Lawrence's career, it's unclear what type of fantasy producer he truly is. Lawrence finished 17th in per-game fantasy production in 2023. Last year also marked the second straight season he finished strong, as the former top pick was sixth among QBs in fantasy points per game from Week 11 on. Gone is last season's leading receiver in Calvin Ridley, but the team still has some savvy skill players to support a return to relevance for the Lawrence in Year 4. While he is talented as a runner, a lack of designed rushing plays and a greater reliance on pocket production has him understandably positioned on the fringes of QB1 and QB2 status as 2024 fantasy drafts approach. It will only take a middle-to-late-round pick to find out if Lawrence can sustain a full season of special production.

outlooksByWeek.1: Brock Bowers was the first tight end off the board in the 2024 Draft, going 13th overall to the Raiders, and that seemed like a bargain given his elite athleticism and tremendous production at Georgia. Bowers isn't just a pass-catching H-back style of tight end either, showing an affinity for blocking that should keep him on the field in all situations. He will have to cede some volume to 2023 second-round pick Michael Mayer, as Las Vegas features the most impressive young TE duo in the league, but Bowers is the superior prospect and the team's lack of established, dynamic playmakers behind Davante Adams could give both tight ends plenty of opportunities to make an impact. Bowers will look to make a splashy NFL debut in Week 1 against a Chargers defense that ranked in the bottom half of the league last year in receptions and receiving yards allowed to TEs.

player.seasonOutlook: The top tight end prospect in this year's draft class, Bowers landed in a puzzling spot, selected 13th overall by the Raiders, who already had 2023 second-rounder Michael Mayer (plus Davante Adams and Jakobi Meyers at wide receiver). Though a high-ankle sprain cost him four games of his final season at Georgia, Bowers posted stunning receiving numbers during a three-year career there: 175 receptions, 2,538 yards and 26 touchdowns, all easily FBS position bests, plus 8.9 yards after the catch per reception. He should immediately grab a prominent role in the Raiders' offense, though Mayer's presence could cut into his snaps, especially if Bowers struggles to adapt to the blocking chores of the position initially. Nevertheless, he has legitimate TE1 upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jake Elliott is coming off a career-best campaign in which he connected on 30-of-32 field goals for Philadelphia.  The proficiency of the Eagles offense inside the red zone has actually been a detriment to Elliott's overall numbers, though, as Elliott has had to settle for extra points instead of field goals on many occasions.  Philadelphia's offense should be as potent as ever with the addition of Saquon Barkley, though, so opportunities should remain plentiful regardless.  In Week 1, the Eagles face a Packers squad that allowed 20.6 points per tilt in 2023, which was 10th in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: Elliott's seventh NFL season was his most accurate, and it included a career-best seven field goals of 50 yards or more. Elliott also reached 44 extra points made for the third consecutive season, a stretch no other kicker can match. The eighth-most accurate kicker on field goals all time, Elliott doesn't always get the volume of his peers, thanks to Philadelphia's red zone efficiency and desire to go for it (and succeed) on fourth downs. He signed a four-year contract extension and figures to be one of the most reliable, safe kickers in the sport yet again. Elliott won't be the first kicker off the board, but he definitely belongs in the top 10.

The Saints D/ST finished as the ninth best in fantasy last season on the strength of 29 takeaways (fourth most in the NFL) and three touchdowns. The mountains were high (six weeks with at least 12 fantasy points) and the valleys were low (seven weeks with four or fewer points), and as we enter the 2024 season, many of their top players are getting long in the tooth, which is cause for concern. But if they can stay healthy and improve the pass rush (34 sacks ranked tied for 28th), this unit may have another top-10 run in the tank.

outlooksByWeek.1: CeeDee Lamb is fresh off a lucrative contract extension and should be primed for another huge season in Dallas as the undisputed top option.  Dak Prescott returns under center, and the tandem connected for career-best numbers for Lamb in 2023.  Lamb caught a staggering 135 passes for 1,749 yards and 12 touchdowns.  With a lackluster running game and limited depth behind Lamb at wideout, the star wideout should see all the opportunities he can handle.  Unfortunately, Week 1 may provide a stiff test, as Lamb not only may not be in game shape yet due to signing the extension late, but Dallas will also face a Cleveland pass defense that allowed the fewest yards in the NFL last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Lamb led the entire fantasy football world in fantasy points last season, surpassing 25 points in eight games and truly dominating the second half of the season. Lamb started slow -- a career theme, actually -- but from Week 8 on, he averaged 28.5 fantasy points per game. His 313.6 fantasy points in the final 11 weeks alone topped the full-season performance of all but nine NFL players. Lamb is not only a clear top-five fantasy pick, but with his durability and the Cowboys' high-octane offense, one can make the case for him as a solid choice to go No. 1 overall.

outlooksByWeek.1: Travis Kelce failed to reach 1,000 receiving yards last year for the first time since 2015, but he remains the top target for Patrick Mahomes in Kansas City's passing game. The 34-year-old tight end began to show his age in 2023, as his 10.6 yards per reception was a career low, but he's seen over 120 targets for seven straight seasons, and that seems unlikely to change. Kelce's efficiency could also improve if new deep threats Xavier Worthy and Marquise Brown are able to take the top off defenses, opening up the middle of the field. Kelce faces a tough test in Week 1 against a Ravens defense that gave up only three touchdowns to tight ends in 2023, tied for second in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: The stats back Kelce as best tight end in fantasy football history. He has 2,116.7 points since 2016, by far the most any tight end has scored over an eight-year period, and he has six positional first-place finishes in that span, never finishing worse than third. Still, Kelce's detractors cite his 10.6 yards per reception and 12.9% big-play rates from 2023, both the worst of his NFL career. We counter that the Chiefs' problems at wide receiver put oodles of pressure on him to perform, and made it easier for opponents to defend him. Kelce's days of being a mid-first-round pick and virtual TE1 lock might be behind him, but he's still Patrick Mahomes' go-to guy and plenty capable of a 2023 repeat.

outlooksByWeek.1: Lamar Jackson posted the highest yards per attempt and completion rate of his career in 2023, his first under offensive coordinator Todd Monken. That was good enough for him to win his second MVP Award and he'll now lead Baltimore into a Week 1 matchup against a stout Chiefs defense. The secondary has had some turnover between the losses of L'Jarius Sneed and Mike Edwards, but there's still athleticism at all levels of the unit. That athleticism could serve to limit Jackson's usefulness on the ground, though the Ravens will undoubtedly have to utilize an aggressive offensive approach to keep pace with Patrick Mahomes. That should lead to serviceable statistical output for Jackson to begin 2024.

player.seasonOutlook: The reigning NFL MVP enters his seventh pro season as one of the league's most dynamic players at the position. In 2023, working under new offensive coordinator Todd Monken, Jackson played in 16 games, posting a career high in pass yards, while leading all quarterbacks in rushing. He averaged 20.7 fantasy points per game, finishing as QB4 in total points. With a strong supporting cast led by tight end Mark Andrews, wide receiver Zay Flowers and running back Derrick Henry, plus a system that maximizes his elite dual-threat ability, Jackson should once again produce top-tier fantasy numbers.

outlooksByWeek.1: James Cook will look to pick up where he left off for the Bills in a Week 1 matchup against the Cardinals. He recorded double-digit carries in the final 10 games, leading to a 1,122-yard sophomore campaign while adding a solid 44 receptions. The downside is that Cook only ran for two touchdowns while Josh Allen got 15. While you wouldn't expect Allen to replicate that, Buffalo added Ray Davis to their backfield via the draft who offers more size and power that can be used closer to the goal line. Cook's volume should remain steady and the matchup to open the year couldn't be softer as Arizona gave up the most rushing yards in the league in 2023 and didn't substantially upgrade defensively. We just need to see more scoring chances for Cook for him to take off.

player.seasonOutlook: Cook returns to the gridiron for his third season with the Bills. He finished as RB12 in fantasy last season and ranked fourth in the league in rushing yards. Joe Brady replacing Ken Dorsey as offensive coordinator was a godsend for Cook. From Weeks 11 through 18, Cook averaged and impressive 19.6 touches and 16.4 fantasy points per game. Since Cook is the undisputed leader of the Bills' backfield, we can expect a similar workload from him in 2024. He can be safely drafted as a high-end RB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: DK Metcalf starts Week 1 against the Broncos, who had the 24th ranked passing defense last season. Metcalf led the Seahawks with 1,114 receiving yards overall and 7.4 targets per game in 2023. Seattle's new offensive coordinator Ryan Grubb is well-known for his high volume passing attack at the University of Washington, so Metcalf should continue to see plenty of targets from Geno Smith.  While Metcalf will have to deal with coverage from shutdown corner Patrick Surtain, Denver didn't make many meaningful moves to improve their defense that allowed 29 receiving TDs last season, fifth most in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: Despite missing the first game of his five-year career and, at times, struggling to connect with Geno Smith, Metcalf posted his second consecutive season of more than 1,000 receiving yards. The SPARQ standout led the team in target percentage (23%) with a healthy number of looks occurring in the red area of the field (24). Metcalf also thrived as the team's primary deep threat, averaging more than 95 air yards per game (WR12) while recording a career-best 16.9 YPR (WR6). His upside is overwhelming and figures to be clearly baked into his top-20 positional ADP.

outlooksByWeek.1: James Conner faces a Bills defense in Week 1 that was average against the run in 2023, ranking 15th overall in rushing defense. Conner was the Cardinals' primary red zone option last season, with 3.1 red zone opportunities per game in 2023. Those valuable opportunities might be scarce since they are underdogs against the Bills' high-powered offense. The addition of rookie Trey Benson might also reduce some of Conner's workload. Conner is a solid pass-catcher out of the backfield, but it's worth noting that he split this duty with Emari Demercado towards the end of last season. The Bills allowed 14 rushing touchdowns last season, tied for 12th best in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: Despite missing four games due to a knee issue, Conner emerged as Arizona's most reliable offensive weapon, regularly carrying the load (18 touches per game) and finding surprising efficiency (5.1 YPT, RB16) despite erratic QB play. Conner averaged 80 rush yards per game and cleared 1,000 yards on the ground for the first time in his seven-year career. He also recorded seven rushing scores for the second straight season. At 29 years old and in the final year of his current contract, Conner's time in the desert is likely coming to a close, as evidenced by the team's addition of Trey Benson in the third round of April's draft. The rookie might steal a few snaps and touches from Conner, but the vet figures to see enough volume to garner RB2 consideration.

outlooksByWeek.1: DeVonta Smith has averaged over 1,000 yards receiving and over 13 yards per reception in each of his first three seasons with the Eagles.  Smith also tied with A.J. Brown for seven receiving touchdowns.  Saquon Barkley's addition at running back should only serve to make the Philadelphia offense even more diverse and dynamic.  In Week 1, Philadelphia will face a Packers defense that was fairly stingy against the pass in 2023, allowing just 206.8 yards per tilt through the air, which was ninth in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: Smith surpassed 1,000 receiving yards for the second consecutive season, and enters his fourth NFL season with a secure, three-year contract extension. While fantasy managers may bristle at the 2020 Heisman Trophy winner continuing his statistical success in a loaded offense with Jalen Hurts, Saquon Barkley and A.J. Brown, it hasn't been an issue so far. Smith may not see top target share compared to other elite WRs, but he averaged a career-best 9.5 yards per target and offers a high fantasy floor, having scored double-digit fantasy points in 11 games last season. Consider Smith a fringe WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Chris Godwin will kick off his eighth season in a Buccaneers uniform with a Week 1 matchup at home against the Commanders. The 28-year-old is quietly coming off three consecutive 1,000-yard seasons, though he's scored a combined 10 receiving TDs in that span, as compared to teammate Mike Evans' 13 scores from 2023 alone. Moving back to the slot under new OC Liam Coen could benefit Godwin, who while capable of succeeding on the perimeter, has long been one of the league's absolute best slot receivers. If positive TD regression is to hit Godwin this season, there will be no likelier time than Week 1 against a Washington defense that allowed more points (482) and passing yards (4,457) than any other team in the NFL. If he does primarily operate out of the slot, Godwin will get the benefit of mostly matching up against rookie second-round CB Mike Sainristil.

player.seasonOutlook: Godwin finished last season as fantasy's WR28 and eclipsed 1,000 yards for the third straight season. Baker Mayfield had a solid season and Godwin excelled as a result, but he once again was lacking in the touchdown department and his fantasy upside is impacted by playing in the shadow of Mike Evans. The 28-year-old Godwin still has some life left in his legs, but will have to improve on his 12.3 fantasy points per game if he's going to be more than a WR3 again this season.

The Cowboys D/ST finished tied for first in fantasy points in 2023 (with the Ravens), extending a strong three-year run coinciding with the drafting of dominant edge Micah Parsons, now a three-time Pro Bowler. Dallas led the league in fantasy points in 2021, and was fourth in 2022. Parsons may be the most noticeable talent on defense, but he is hardly alone, with DeMarcus Lawrence, Eric Kendricks, Stephon Gilmore and DaRon Bland, among others. The Cowboys forced 26 turnovers last season and scored seven touchdowns, with Bland responsible for five of them. That rate figures to regress, but the Cowboys should deliver another strong fantasy campaign, perhaps the best in the league again.

outlooksByWeek.1: Christian Watson enters Week 1 looking to rebound after an injury-plagued sophomore season that limited him to just nine games. Despite the missed time, Watson still flashed big-play potential, scoring five touchdowns on only 28 receptions. Unfortunately for Watson, he'll need to contend with Jayden Reed, Romeo Doubs and Dontayvion Wicks for targets within Green Bay's balanced passing attack, making consistent volume a challenge. However, he could see increased opportunities against an Eagles defense that allowed the most fantasy points per game to opposing WRs last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Watson is back in Green Bay as one of the most difficult players to figure out in fantasy. A big-play WR with multiple boom games to his name, Watson was second in points per reception and finished eighth in end zone targets despite playing only nine games last season. The biggest knock against him is his faulty hamstrings, which have kept him from staying on the field thus far in his young career. Watson has missed 11 games over his first two seasons, and he's now in a very full wide receiver room. Watson carries risk, but his ceiling remains off the charts. He's best viewed as a high-upside WR4.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tony Pollard will make his Titans debut in Week 1 against a Bears defense that allowed the third-fewest rushing yards to running backs last season but gave up the most receiving yards in the league to the position. Pollard is expected to fill a 1A role to Tyjae Spears' 1B in the backfield as the Titans begin life after Derrick Henry. Both well-rounded RBs can play on all three downs, but the 215-pound Pollard seems slightly better-suited to goal-line work than the 200-pound Spears, though Pollard struggled to find success between the tackles in his final season with the Cowboys. Pollard dipped from 12 scrimmage TDs on 232 touches in 2022 to six TDs on 307 touches in 2023.

player.seasonOutlook: Even though Pollard enters his sixth season in the NFL, it's fair to ask, just who is this guy? Is he the ultra-efficient game-breaker from his Pro Bowl 2022 effort? Or is he the tailback who struggled to sustain steady production as the Cowboys' lead back last season? The reality could be somewhere between these extremes. The presence of Tyjae Spears is notable, as he consumed 150 touches last season, including the majority of work on third downs. There was room for Derrick Henry to command a major workload in a backfield with Spears, yet Henry is a singular talent and archetype. Given Spears' proficient receiving profile, it's likely Pollard's ability to be efficient on early downs and in the red zone will dictate his fantasy stock this season. Targeting Pollard as a borderline RB2 or flex candidate could still prove rewarding on a team that aggressively went after him in free agency.

outlooksByWeek.1: Rome Odunze, the ninth overall pick in the 2024 draft, begins his rookie season with the Bears as a highly anticipated addition. Known for his impressive combine metrics and strong college production, Odunze faces a competitive receiver room with veterans DJ Moore and Keenan Allen, as well as capable tight ends Cole Kmet and Gerald Everett. While Odunze is expected to be Chicago's No. 3 receiver in terms of playing time, he has the potential to make a significant impact, especially in a high-scoring offense. In Week 1, Odunze will look to get his career off to a strong start against a favorable matchup with a Tennessee defense that allowed the sixth-most fantasy points and the sixth-most receiving yards per game to wide receivers last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Odunze joins the Bears as the ninth overall pick in the 2024 NFL draft. He's a big (6-foot-3, 212 pounds), physical receiver who knows how to use his size and body when making contested catches. He's the real deal and his numbers during his final season at Washington show that (92-1,640-13). Odunze has the makeup of a star in this league, but in 2024 he'll be third in line for targets behind DJ Moore and Keenan Allen. Add in a rookie QB to the mix and a run-heavy scheme and we're looking at a WR4/5 with upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Brandon Aubrey came from virtual anonymity to have a sensational season for the Dallas Cowboys.  Aubrey converted 36-of-38 three-pointers, including all 10 of his field goals from 50-plus yards, and even connected on a 60-yard strike.  He led the NFL in points as a rookie.  Aubrey's combination of accuracy, a strong leg and kicking for a stellar offense should once again vault him to the top of the kicker rankings.  In Week 1, Dallas will face a Cleveland squad that surrendered 21.3 points per tilt in 2023, which was 13th in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: The NFL's leading scorer last season with 157 points and 180 fantasy points, Aubrey's story is quite unprecedented. He played soccer at Notre Dame and two seasons of Major League Soccer before becoming a traditional kicker in the USFL. The Cowboys took a chance and enjoyed a league-leading 36 field goals, including an NFL-record 35 straight to begin his career, and an historic 10-of-10 from 50 yards and beyond. Aubrey didn't miss a field goal until Week 18. Dallas figures to boast one of the top volume offenses again, and Aubrey should see ample opportunities for extra points and field goals. Make him one of the first kickers off your draft board, if not the first.

outlooksByWeek.1: Justin Herbert is coming off the worst season of his NFL career, as he missed four games due to a finger injury and set career lows with a 65.1 percent completion percentage, 3.134 passing yards and just 20 passing touchdowns. Things aren't pointed in the right direction for 2024, either. Herbert battled a plantar fascia issue in training camp which threatens to limit his mobility, and the Chargers' switch to Jim Harbaugh as head coach and Greg Roman as offensive coordinator should bring a much more run-heavy approach, denying the quarterback the high volume he's accustomed to. Herbert figures to be under center in Week 1 despite the foot injury, but he'll be facing a Raiders defense that finished in the top half of the league last year in passing yards and passing TDs allowed.

player.seasonOutlook: While Herbert is one of the league's most talented quarterbacks, he is saddled with starting for a Jim Harbaugh rebuild that's precariously thin on receiving talent. In the past three seasons, Herbert is third in passing yards per game (274.1), fourth among qualifiers in Total QBR (65.3) and he has averaged 19.1 fantasy points per game. That latter number placed eighth at the position, in large part because Herbert couldn't get things done behind a sputtering running game and with Mike Williams and Keenan Allen missing time due to injury in 2023. Allen and Williams are now elsewhere, and Harbaugh appears committed to a run-oriented offense. Herbert might struggle to deliver the fantasy goods, making him more of a matchup play for 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Ja'Marr Chase enjoyed a productive 2023 season despite playing half of it with backup quarterback Jake Browning. There's little left for him to prove to cement his status as one of the top wide receivers in the game, though his status for the Bengals' Week 1 matchup against the Patriots is less clear. Chase has held out from the majority of training camp while seeking a new contract, and he has yet to practice leading up to the team's regular season opener. If he does suit up, he could face a pitch count, though he'd still likely be worth starting due to his explosive playmaking ability.

player.seasonOutlook: Chase starts his fourth pro season with the Bengals looking to boost his numbers with a healthy Joe Burrow back running the offense. Chase averaged 16.4 fantasy PPG, down from the 20.0 PPG he registered in 2022 (WR3). However, Chase still posted five games with 20 or more points, including the 52.2-point performance in Week 5 versus the Cardinals. Chase has totaled 29 touchdowns in his career and is one the league's premier players at the position due to his big-play ability and upper-tier play strength. Lock him in as a top 10 player overall in fantasy this season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jahmyr Gibbs enters his second season as the Lions' lead back after a strong rookie year, showcasing his ability as both a runner (5.2 YPC, 10 TDs) and a receiver. With David Montgomery likely serving as the 1B option, Gibbs is positioned to be the primary playmaker in the backfield. Detroit's excellent offensive line will continue to create opportunities, though Gibbs might see fewer goal-line carries due to Montgomery's power-running role. In Week 1, Gibbs faces a Rams defense that was tough against the run last season, allowing only 77.5 rushing yards per game to opposing RBs, ranking 8th in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: Gibbs dispelled any draft-day doubts by finishing as fantasy's RB10 in his rookie season. The 12th overall pick in 2023 showcased his explosiveness in a Lions offense that had the second-most RB rushing yards and attempts. Gibbs had six weeks inside the top three at RB, finished second in yards before first contact and was fifth in fantasy points per touch. Despite being in a committee with David Montgomery, Gibbs was also 12th in scrimmage yards, ninth in total touchdowns and top 10 in targets and receptions. All this while ranking 25th among RBs in touches. He won't have the workload of a feature back, but at just 22 years old, Gibbs is already a superstar and should be viewed as a clear top-10 RB.

outlooksByWeek.1: Mike Evans, ever the pillar of consistency, will begin the road to a hopeful 11th consecutive 1,000-yard campaign with the Buccaneers in a tasty Week 1 matchup against Washington. As Evans looks to build off a tremendous campaign in which he emerged as quarterback Baker Mayfield's favorite target and scored 13 of Tampa Bay's 28 receiving touchdowns, Evans couldn't ask for a better matchup than the Commanders, whose defense led the league last season in points and yards given up. As a cherry on top, Washington parted ways with standout cornerback Kendall Fuller. None of top CBs Benjamin St-Juste, Michael Davis and Emmanuel Forbes can be confident matching up with Evans. Expect new OC Liam Coen's debut with the Buccaneers to heavily feature dialing up Evans' number.

player.seasonOutlook: Evans is entering his 11th NFL season (all with Tampa Bay) after signing an extension during the offseason. The future Hall of Famer has produced 1,000-plus receiving yards in each of his first 10 seasons and actually posted the third-most receiving yards and matched the second-highest TD total of his career in 2023. Evans' seventh-place finish in fantasy points marked his best finish since 2016 and he's never finished a campaign worse than 23rd. Evans is nearing the end of his career, but at age-31, he likely still has another year of high-end play left in the tank. As long as Baker Mayfield is under center, Evans will remain, at worst, a good WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Mark Andrews was involved in a car accident in mid-August but has since returned to practice and appears to be ready to play for Baltimore's Week 1 matchup against the Chiefs. That continued his run of bad luck, as he was forced to miss the final six games of the 2023 regular season as well as the team's Divisional Round playoff matchup against the Texans due to an ankle injury caused by the now-banned hip drop tackle. When Andrews was able to take the field, he remained a highly targeted option in the offense. Assuming he is able to play a full snap count, Andrews could be in for a solid Week 1 performance as the Chiefs have relatively inexperienced options such as Chamarri Conner and Bryan Cook that are likely to see a significant number of snaps covering Andrews.

player.seasonOutlook: Still in his prime playing years, Andrews heads into his seventh season with the Ravens. Andrews played in only 10 games last season (ankle), but he averaged 13.2 PPG, while seeing 14 red zone targets. Andrews is a natural seam stretcher with the frame to win contested catches, and he will continue to be a prime option for quarterback Lamar Jackson as a middle-of-the-field option with third-level ability on schemed concepts. Andrews is a top-three player at the position.

outlooksByWeek.1: DJ Moore begins his second season in Chicago as the team's primary receiving target. Moore topped 1,000 yards for the first time in his career last year, setting personal bests in catches (96), total yards (1,385), and touchdowns (nine). Despite increased target competition this season, Moore's role as the No. 1 option should keep him heavily involved. In Week 1, he'll face a Titans defense that allowed the sixth-most fantasy points and the sixth-most receiving yards per game to wide receivers last year, presenting a promising opportunity for a strong start.

player.seasonOutlook: Moore is the WR1 in Chicago after delivering the best fantasy season of his career in 2023, setting career highs in receptions, receiving yards and receiving touchdowns. It helped that he saw 15 end zone targets, good enough for sixth most at the position. Moore will look to continue his NFC North dominance while splitting targets with Keenan Allen and rookie Rome Odunze. Add to that a rookie QB in Caleb Williams and you've got yourself a wide receiver with top-10 talent but a ranking closer to WR20.

outlooksByWeek.1: Joe Burrow appears to be fully recovered from wrist surgery that ended his 2023 season prematurely and will lead the Bengals into a Week 1 matchup against New England. However, there's still a cloud over the Cincinnati offense as Ja'Marr Chase continues his hold-in, leaving his status murky for the game and potentially leaving Burrow without his top pass catcher. The New England secondary also has the chance to be respectable as both Jonathan Jones and Christian Gonzalez are capable players in coverage. That makes Burrow something of a risky start, though he's topped 30 passing touchdowns in each of his last two full seasons.

player.seasonOutlook: Heading into his fifth pro season, Burrow looks to rebound after an injury-plagued 2023 that limited his production and availability. A calf injury during training camp forced Burrow to miss practice time, while a wrist injury in Week 11 shut him down for the season. From Weeks 1-4, with Burrow clearly still impacted by the calf injury, he averaged only 7.9 fantasy points per game. However, from Weeks 5-10, he posted three games of 22 or more points, with an average of 21.4 points during that stretch. With two big-play receivers in Ja'Marr Chase and Tee Higgins, a healthy Burrow should be in the mix to produce top-five quarterback numbers in the Bengals' pass-heavy offense.

outlooksByWeek.1: Calvin Ridley will make his Titans debut in a Week 1 road matchup against a Chicago defense that allowed the ninth-fewest yards to wide receivers last season but tied for the sixth-most touchdowns allowed to the position. After sitting out the 2022 season, Ridley returned to the NFL with 1,016 receiving yards for the Jaguars in 2023 before signing a four-year, $92 million contract with the Titans in March. Ridley is expected to be the top target for second-year QB Will Levis but figures to see a heavy dose of standout Bears cornerback Jaylon Johnson, especially if fellow Tennessee WR DeAndre Hopkins (knee) isn't 100 percent.

player.seasonOutlook: Joining the Titans in free agency via a rich new pact was a bit surprising, and also very interesting. Ridley's return to NFL action in 2023 resulted in a somewhat volatile season in Jacksonville. He had seven games with at least 83 receiving yards and nine with 40 yards or fewer. A sluggish catch rate of 55.9% (lowest among the top 40 in targets) was a key culprit. The Titans paid Ridley handsomely to help open the downfield offense next to DeAndre Hopkins, while aiding Will Levis' progression as a professional passer. Much like last season, a blend of volume and variance is likely the story with Ridley. There will be valleys, but also impressive peaks. Taking on Ridley in the middle rounds on the fringes of WR2 and WR3 pricing could prove rewarding.

outlooksByWeek.1: Aaron Jones begins the 2024 season as the Vikings' lead back after moving on from Green Bay, where he finished last year with a strong string of performances despite battling injuries. While the shift to Minnesota could be a downgrade in terms of offensive efficiency with Sam Darnold under center, Jones may see an increase in snaps given the limited competition behind him. He gets a favorable matchup in Week 1, facing a Giants defense that allowed 4.59 yards per carry to opposing running backs last season, ranking 30th in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: Jones joins the Vikings after spending his first seven seasons with the Packers. The 29-year-old is coming off of his least-productive season since his rookie year, missing six games due to a hamstring injury and MCL sprain. Jones is looking to rebound for a Vikings team desperately in need of punch at the position, after their RBs ranked 30th in scrimmage yards and touchdowns last season. Jones' touchdowns and fantasy points per game have decreased four years in a row. Still, Jones will be the RB1 in a Vikings offense that will use him in both the running and passing game. With that dual-purpose workload and a high likelihood for positive touchdown regression, Jones is best viewed as a low-end RB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Keenan Allen begins his first season with the Bears after a standout 2023 campaign with the Chargers. Despite setting career highs in yards per game (95.6) and PPR scoring average (21.5) last year, Allen was traded to Chicago following a contract dispute. While his new role may not guarantee the same target dominance as in Los Angeles, Allen will still be a key part of a revamped Bears offense alongside DJ Moore, rookie Rome Odunze, and other pass-catching options. In Week 1, Allen faces a Tennessee defense that allowed the sixth-most fantasy points and the sixth-most receiving yards per game to wide receivers last year, offering a favorable matchup for a strong debut.

player.seasonOutlook: Allen joins the Bears after spending the past 11 seasons with the Chargers. A dominant possession receiver, Allen is coming off the second-best fantasy season and the highest points per game mark of his storied career. Now at 32 years old and starting over with rookie QB Caleb Williams, Allen's best fantasy days are likely behind him. And while he's still a legitimate threat, Allen is now in a crowded WR room with an inexperienced signal-caller, so he should be viewed as a WR3 heading into the season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Kyler Murray starts the season with a Week 1 showdown against a Bills defense that had 16 interceptions in 2023, tied for 6th most in the league. The Cardinals gave Murray a premium new receiving weapon in rookie Marvin Harrison, and he still gets to take advantage of one of the best receiving tight ends in the league in Trey McBride. Murray might rush and scramble a bit more this season now that he is a year and a half removed from his ACL surgery, which would be a nice boost to his fantasy floor.
