With Harrison now in the fold, the Cardinals 27th ranked passing offense last year should improve, but it's a very tough matchup in Buffalo. The Bills defense lost some key players in the secondary this offseason, but they are typically one of the stronger pass defenses in the league, ranking 6th in passing yards allowed last year.

player.seasonOutlook: Murray returned as the Cardinals' starter after being sidelined for 11 months due to a right knee injury that he suffered in December 2022. Murray's rehab proved successful, as the dual-threat talent immediately flashed his trademark wheels, averaging more than 30 rushing yards per game between Weeks 10 and 18 last season. He was less consistent as a passer, recording his lowest completion percentage since his 2019 rookie campaign. A considerable amount of his inefficiency, however, could be attributed to a dearth of surrounding talent, as well as Marquise Brown's end-of-season absence (heel). Murray heads into his sixth pro campaign with a full offseason under his belt and plenty of time to build rapport with the team's young pass-catching talent, including fourth overall pick Marvin Harrison Jr. Consider Murray a low-end QB1 for fantasy purposes.

outlooksByWeek.1: Ezekiel Elliott returns to the Cowboys on a one-year deal, but it would be foolish to expect his production in 2024 to mirror his glory days with Dallas.  Elliott appeared in all 17 games for the Patriots in 2023 but managed career lows of 642 yards and three touchdowns on the ground, along with an average of a paltry 3.5 yards per tote.  While he did catch 51 balls for 313 yards out of the backfield, Elliott will also have to contend with Rico Dowdle in the Dallas backfield, as the duo appears set to split touches.  In Week 1, the tandem will take on a rather stout Cleveland run defense which allowed just 105.5 yards per tilt on the ground in 2023, which was 11th in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: After one underwhelming season with an even more underwhelming Patriots offense, the 29-year-old Elliott signed back with the Cowboys, days after the franchise spent its draft picks on other positions. He will battle holdovers Rico Dowdle and Deuce Vaughn for touches. Elliott used to be one of the first picks in a fantasy draft, but his last RB1 season was 2019. He scored a solid 12 touchdowns during each of his final two inefficient seasons with Dallas, though, and he showed he can still catch passes last season in New England's terrible offense, so perhaps RB2 production remains attainable. Just don't draft him as an RB2.

Hockenson is back for his third season with the Vikings after tearing his ACL and MCL in Week 16 last season. It was an unfortunate end to an otherwise spectacular season for the superstar tight end. A top-five tight end in three of the past four seasons, the biggest question is how many games Hockenson will miss as he rehabs from this injury. Loosely projected to miss the first four to six weeks of the season, while likely playing with a rookie QB, means Hockenson checks in outside the top 12 at the TE position. He should be drafted late in all formats, as he could return to the TE1 mix during the season.

The Ravens are going through a transition after the departure of coordinator Mike Macdonald, but new defensive play caller Zach Orr takes over a unit that averaged 10.1 fantasy PPG last season (tied for the most with Dallas), while leading the league in sacks and points allowed per game (16.4). Using a mix of coverage and disguised pressure, the Ravens have talent at all three levels of the field, with defensive tackle Justin Madabuike, linebacker Roquan Smith and safety Kyle Hamilton leading the way. The coordinator change could lead to some bumps early in the season, but the Ravens have the players to produce as a top-five fantasy defense once again.

outlooksByWeek.1: Greg Zuerlein will seek additional opportunities when the Jets face the 49ers in Week 1 Monday night. Zuerlien has attempted 37 and 38 field goal attempts over the last two years, slightly above league average, but his fantasy floor has been limited by the team's previous quarterback play, as he attempted just 16 PATs last year. For as long as Aaron Rodgers is healthy, that should change and raise his weekly potential. It's a challenging opening opponent with the 49ers having allowed the fourth fewest points last season, but the game should be competitive, enabling 3-point chances while 1-point chances won't be void.

player.seasonOutlook: Zuerlein enters his third season with the Jets. He made 35 of 38 field goals last season, his most accurate campaign (92.1%) since 2017. The Jets struggled without Aaron Rodgers under center, finishing the season ranked 31st in total yards and 29th in points scored per game. With Rodgers back under center in 2024, the Jets should be much better on offense, which will give Zuerlein a considering higher scoring floor. He should be viewed as a top-10 fantasy kicker.

outlooksByWeek.1: J.K. Dobbins has been healthy for only nine regular-season games over the last three seasons due to serious knee and Achilles injuries, derailing what had been a promising beginning to an NFL career. As a rookie in 2020, he averaged an eye-popping 6.0 yards per carry, but there's no way to know how much of that explosiveness he has left until he tests himself in game action. Dobbins signed a one-year contract with the Chargers to re-unite with offensive coordinator Greg Roman, his OC in Baltimore for that rookie season, but he'll be fighting for snaps and touches with former teammate Gus Edwards as well as rookie Kimani Vidal. Dobbins arguably has the most theoretical upside of that trio, but his workload could be limited as Los Angeles tries to keep him healthy. In Week 1, Dobbins will face a Raiders defense that finished in the bottom 10 in rushing yards allowed and rushing TDs allowed to running backs last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Dobbins is another piece brought to Los Angeles as the Chargers assembled a sort of "Ravens West." Dobbins should compete with Gus Edwards, Isaiah Spiller and rookie Kimani Vidal in what's sure to be a heavily utilized running back corps. Dobbins is the ultimate risk/reward pickup. In 13 career games with double-digit carries, his 6.2 YPC and nine rushing touchdowns underscore his upside, but his 43 absences in 67 NFL contests serve as a reminder of his propensity for injury. Dobbins did his best work in Baltimore under Greg Roman, the offensive coordinator with whom he is now reunited, so monitor Dobbins' preseason and be prepared to pounce on him as a late-round value pick if he's looking good.
